ations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4f5cd96a26b09e33fea73f78da8891c21509f5cf0bce77e0b4531f479bb4d03f"}, "3": {"node_id": "85b15ca4-9b81-4aa8-ab77-b1558ec6542a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "df0bb26afea7373826ad0b656f7488528381802930c074509681c885b8d75412"}}, "hash": "7a14793e4d4ea0e3d9d6317de9d8d716d22fbebb10edab4a133af069d56fe6a0", "text": "each country. In other words, it is a move to a kind of \u2018a la carte development policy menu\u201d. 15 Chang (2005). 16 Gallagher (2007). 17 Ostry (2002). 18 General Agreement of Trade in Services (2002). 6 regulations across sectors and countries, and ensuring policy coherence19 at the global and national levels, have emerged as important guiding principles in the context of trade liberalization and influence the exercise of policy space. Trade negotiations across different levels have tended to put an overriding emphasis on increasing market access (MA) and trade flows per se often without adequate reference to a balancing of development costs and benefits. Trade-related obligations have had direct and indirect implications on exercise of policy space in several countries and often without any accompanying increase in MA, underlining the need to exercise caution where tangible trade offs for policy space do not exist.20 The Sao-Paulo consensus during the 11th Session of the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) in 2004, highlighted that countries should bear in mind the development goals and objectives, and take into account the need for appropriate balance between national policy space and international disciplines and commitments in trade, investment and industrial development.21 Striking the right balance however is not easy as the UNCTAD World Investment Report (WIR), 2001 noted as well: \u2018too much policy space reduces the value of international obligations; too stringent obligations place excessive constraints on the national policy space. Finding the right balance is the challenge\u2019. 22 3.1 Understanding policy space The usage of the term \u2018policy space\u2019 is often traced back to discussions at UNCTAD acquiring an \u2018official\u2019 sta- tus when it was defined in the Sao Paulo Consensus, 200423 document as \u2018the scope for domestic policies, especially in the areas of trade, investment and industrial development\u2026 often framed by international disciplines, commitments, and global market considerations\u2019.24 While the term itself may be of recent vintage, policy space in a broad sense has been practiced by most developing countries inter alia for broad economic strategy and specific policies. It embodies international policies, which underlie the work of the UNCTAD since long and is a \u2018fusion of three key principles in international law\u201925: \uf06c Principle of Sovereign Equality of States, which refers to the binding nature and application of interna- tional rules and disciplines dependent on the equal exercise of national sovereignty by participating States. \uf06c Right to Development. \uf06c Principle of Special Treatment for Developing Countries, which relates to provision of special and dif- ferential treatment in order to be responsive and accommodating to specific development needs and circumstances rather than be based on a one-size-fits-all approach. Policy space may also be understood as the scope for domestic policies to ensure equity, strategic intervention and regulation especially in the areas of trade, investment and industrial development. It can be framed, constrained or expanded by the international commitments, agreements and disciplines that states 19 The term \u2018policy coherence\u2019 is a multi-dimensional term which can lend itself to varying meanings. The term is used here in the context of \u2018reinforcing coherence between national development strategies and global processes and discipline as well as policy coherence among and within the various sectors of the global economy that impact on development prospects of developing countries especially important in the context the interface between the international trading system and the international monetary and financial system\u2019. See for more details, UNCTAD (2004). 20 Corrales-Leal (2007). 21 UNCTAD (2004). \u201cS\u00e3o Paulo Consensus\u201d. TD/410, http://www.unctad.org/en/docs/td410_en.pdf, accessed 24 November 2007. 22 UNCTAD (2001). 23 ODI (2007). 24 UNCTAD (2004). \u201cS\u00e3o Paulo Consensus\u201d. TD/410, http://www.unctad.org/en/docs/td410_en.pdf, accessed 24 November 2007. 25 South Centre (2006). 7 may choose to enter into and which they have to implement consistent with the international law principle of pacta sunt servanda.26 Changing domestic resource constraints and international commitments have strong implications on the effectiveness of national policy space, i.e. on the range of policy choices available to countries.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "85b15ca4-9b81-4aa8-ab77-b1558ec6542a": {"__data__": {"id_": "85b15ca4-9b81-4aa8-ab77-b1558ec6542a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_UR