Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f0e2b757389047771958f047462d2613a66628b4a490cf27bdd9e3571ecca951"}, "3": {"node_id": "43d64b98-816f-4dc1-bf1c-3a52e97e5ba8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a320622ef1ac7cea1f7dbad23b413b62c212f1cc67529bcfdb285bcebad563a3"}}, "hash": "d794bc1e200391c35873be846d643ae4b7e44fdf40c75b76c0fdd36b9784bf48", "text": "goods, services trade is not a faceless phenomenon across all modes of services supply. Trade in services often takes place via the movement of primary factors of production (people or capital) or via other technologies, which substitute for factor movement, like direct connections through telecommunications and the internet. Consumers may also move to buy services at the place of their production.29 Trade and investment in services has grown at a faster rate than merchandise trade, and has been mainly driven by lower transport costs, advances in telecommunications and information technology and gradual reduction of barriers. The GATS agreement of the WTO, for the first time, brought the services sector in the ambit of the international trading system. GATS offered a four fold categorization of services supply: \uf06c Mode-1: cross-border movement of the service (\u201ccross border trade\u201d) e.g.: e-learning, virtual universities. \uf06c Mode-2: cross-border movement of the service consumer (\u201cconsumption abroad\u201d); e.g.: tourism abroad, students going abroad to study. \uf06c Mode-3: cross-border movement of the corporate service provider through investments (\u201ccommercial presence\u201d); e.g. a particular country allowing foreign companies to buy domestic enterprises, setting up offices, franchises with local organizations. \uf06c Mode-4: \u201ccross border movement of natural persons\u201d; e.g. nurses, teachers and others working abroad temporarily. In principle, the overall architecture of GATS was intended to follow the \u2018request\u2019 and \u2018offer\u2019 mode and the positive listing approach wherein countries retain the flexibilities to voluntarily select both the extent and pace of liberalization in keeping with their developmental goals and needs. References to policy space were made specifically in the preamble to the GATS agreement, besides Article IV and Article XIX. The preamble notes that the objective of an early achievement of progressively higher levels of liberalization of trade in 26 This principle states that every treaty in force is binding upon the parties to it and must be performed by them in good faith. This principle is provided for in terms of the treaty law in Article 26 of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties, 1969, and is subscribed to by all States both as a matter of treaty law and as a matter of customary international law. Applicability of the pacta sunt servanda principle is implicit in para 8 of the Sao Paulo Consensus, when it speaks of the need for \u201cappropriate balance between national policy space and international commitments\u201d. 27 South Centre (2005). 28 Also see Warren (1996). 29 Findlay and Guo (2007). 8 services through successive negotiating rounds while seeking to secure an overall balance of rights and obli- gations needs to respect national policy objectives. Also, the preamble recognizes the right of governments to regulate and introduce new regulations on the supply of services within their territories to meet national policy objectives. Article IV, dealing with the increasing participation of developing countries, mandates that negotiations of specific commitments shall be facilitated in sectors and modes of supply of export interest to developing countries. Article IV.3. also notes that special priority shall be given to the LDC members in the implementation of Article IV by taking particular account of the serious difficulty of the LDCs in accepting negotiated specific commitments in view of their special economic situation and their development, trade and financial needs. Article XIX.2. states that the process of liberalization shall take place with due respect for national policy objectives and the level of development of individual members overall and in individual sectors. Also, it lays down that there shall be appropriate flexibility for individual developing countries for opening fewer sectors, liberalizing fewer types of transactions, progressively extending MA in line with their development situation and when making access to their markets available to foreign services suppliers attaching access conditions aimed at achieving the objectives referred to in Article IV. The GATS agreement in Article XXI relating to modification of schedules however, erects in practical terms, prohibitively high barriers for withdrawal of commitments if the actual experience of liberalization of the country is not found to be beneficial in particular sectors and modes. Article XXI.2 (b) in particular mandates that in the event of a scenario of modification of schedules, countries would need to make com- pensatory adjustments on a MFN basis. In addition, the LDCs have been mandated under the WTO to exercise additional flexibilities as far as policy space under GATS is concerned.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "43d64b98-816f-4dc1-bf1c-3a52e97e5ba8": {"__data__": {"id_": "43d64b98-816f-4dc1-bf1c-3a52e97e5ba8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f0e2b757389047771958f047462d2613a66628b4a490cf27bdd9e3571ecca951"}, "2": {"node_id": "a61709b7-165c-433e-9c1a-3b787a39688a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d794bc1e200391c35873be846d643ae4b7e44fdf40c75b76c0fdd36b9784bf48"}}, "hash": "a320622ef1ac7cea1f7dbad23b413b62c212f1cc67529bcfdb285bcebad563a3", "text": "In the Special Session of the Council for Trade in Services on 3 Sep- tember 2003, modalities for the special treatment for LDC members in the negotiations on trade in services were adopted in the WTO as mandated by Article XIX of t