tate explicitly that the LDCs shall be provided maximum flexibility and shall form the basis for the negotiations. Specifically, the scope of the modalities suggested that restraint would be exercised for removal of MA conditions which LDCs need for achievement of development objectives. Paragraphs 3 and 9 of Annex C of the Hong Kong Ministerial Text (HKMT), mandate members to pursue the \u201cfull and effective implementa- tion of the LDC modalities\u201d.31 Further, in paragraph 26 of the HKMT, it is stated that in light of the particular economic situation of LDCs, including the difficulties they face, the LDCs are not expected to undertake new commitments in GATS. However, as shall be discussed in subsequent sections, in reality the LDC modalities have yet to be realized in practice except in some isolated instances.32 However, the original architecture of GATS has come under increasing strain by industrialized countries led by the European Union (EU) during the Doha negotiations. Since the Sixth WTO Ministerial Conference in Hong Kong in December 2005, the industrialized countries succeeded in introducing a number of important changes in the HKMT which effectively have served to modify the original intent and approach especially with 30 Visit http://www.wto.org/english/news_e/pres03_e/pr351_e.htm, accessed 25 November 2007. 31 Visit http://www.wto.org/english/thewto_e/minist_e/min05_e/final_text_e.htm, accessed 25 November 2007. 32 Norway, for instance, has stated that by way of implementation of the LDC modalities, it has withdrawn all requests to LDCs in services negotiations. See for details, Statement by Norway to the Council for Trade in Services Special Session, 23 June, 2006, http://www.norway- geneva.org/wto/wtodoha/dohaservices/services230606.htm, accessed 25 November 2007. See also a statement from an NGO in Bangladesh on the contra indications to the letter and spirit of the LDC modalities, www.cuts-international.org/documents/Services_Negotiations--