consider\u2019 requests while submitting revised offers on an MFN basis. This is understood to increase the pressure on developing countries further.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3f9631de-b70b-4f44-857f-2faef3d69f5c": {"__data__": {"id_": "3f9631de-b70b-4f44-857f-2faef3d69f5c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c112495ceb6ac8ce80f42861dbfa58325ba385cbcae996edb361ef17e3a21f03"}, "2": {"node_id": "332bb6d6-6d07-4fb2-a082-e8f4830eed78", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c3ca640f08fecaf969120be3fda926252d322958f782b5beb92d53d2c1c752dc"}}, "hash": "679a8b4f0456e25e7b36b1f90929aac04cd3771f0459ec3a83df4445cb97e701", "text": "This is understood to increase the pressure on developing countries further. 3.3 Policy space and Mode 3 of GATS The negotiation of commitments at multilateral/regional/bilateral platforms in the services sector has drawn attention to the potential linkages of these commitments on the policy space available with countries. An analysis of modal distribution of commitments during the Uruguay Round of the WTO shows that 50 percent of the unrestricted commitments were made in Mode 235, 30 percent in Mode 1, around 20 percent in Mode 3 and zero percent in Mode 4. The Uruguay Round commitments and the modal distribution of both horizontal and sector specific commitments were asymmetric in nature and were biased towards less contested areas. This paper offers a preliminary analysis of the nature and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f05f8e35-5948-4f28-8ee1-92e24b7cb55b": {"__data__": {"id_": "f05f8e35-5948-4f28-8ee1-92e24b7cb55b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f82b987f307306559637876998750ad043cd14631f635fdf86a5569a204dc541"}, "3": {"node_id": "239eca08-5ee0-43db-9038-cc278d2c5d89", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0832e2a7e297655b7a38916ca99f5f8ebf2bb67c7f6f91afbc471d1f9e2d85c1"}}, "hash": "050dfd5323c0b50167d163c9e3ad960b36a4be12101cf77f4964fc13f3a0cb1f", "text": "scope of commitments undertaken by select Asian countries on commercial presence (Mode 3) with reference to policy space. The inclusion of Mode 3 in the GATS agreement has been widely seen as the first attempt to introduce multilateral rules on investment liberalization in services through the WTO. It must be recalled that earlier attempts to \u201cmultilateralize\u201d investment rules by including the so called \u201cSingapore issues\u201d (including invest- ments) as well as the OECD negotiations of the Multilateral Agreement on Investment (MAI) amongst industri- alized countries have not succeeded. These failures have led the industrialized countries to explore alternative 33 Visit http://www.jmcti.org/2000round/build-in-agenda/service/tn_s_w_055.pdf , accessed November 2007. 34 Visit http://www.unctad.org/en/docs/tdb52l2a3_en.pdf, accessed 25 November 2007. 35 The structure of services in GATS follows 4 different modes of supply as shall be explained later. 10 options for establishing international investment rules and stepping up the pressure on developing countries to commit to it indirectly, albeit confined only to the services sector vide negotiations on Mode 3 in GATS. Mode 3 is economically the most important mode and is estimated to account for more than half of all trade under GATS.36 The economic importance of this mode can be gleaned from the fact that cross border sup- ply of services can be undertaken for limited services, and access regimes in both Mode 1 and 4 are often linked to some form of commercial presence.37 Not only do the services sector constitute the most important segment in the industrialized countries, the current list of Fortune 500 companies contain more service related companies and fewer manufacturing companies seeking new markets through commercial presence in developing coun- tries than in previous decades.38 In this light, the Study sought to focus attention on the preliminary analysis of commitments on Mode 3 to assess the scope and depth of commitments by Asian countries. 36 Adlung and Roy (2005). 37 Adlung and Roy (2005). 38 Visit http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Service_economy, accessed 25 November 2007. 11 Though services trade has been growing in the world, differences exist in services trade indicators of different regions. Services contribute to over 70 percent of employment in industrialized countries and 35 percent in developing countries. Since the year 1990, the share of services in GDP has risen to 72 percent in industrialized countries and to 52 percent in developing countries. However, services represent no more than 20 percent of total trade on Balance of Payments basis.39 Though these figures suggest that the services trade is stronger for industrialized nations, it is important to note that the annual growth rate of services export is eight percent for developing countries, as compared to six percent for industrialized countries. Also, though the share of developing countries in world services export increased from 18 percent to 24 percent from 1990 to 2005, it is only Asia\u2019s share of services trade that has increased while export shares of Latin America, the Caribbean, and Africa have been stagnant.40 Table 1 shows Asia as the third largest exporter and importer of services, after Europe and North America. Table 1: Share in world commercial services trade by region, 2005 (in percentage) Region Exports Imports North America 17 16 South & Central America 3 3 Europe 52 48 Commonwealth of Independent States 2 2 Africa 2 3 Middle East 2 3 Asia 22 25 Source: World Trade Report, 2006. 4. Service trade: Differences within regions 39 Visit http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/serv_e/gatsqa_e.htm, accessed 10 September 2007. 40 Puri (2007). 12 Table 2: Change in share of services output 