": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "57df26ded1927372b2b90b2f230d79892aea4aaac93d2e72f247f49615f6a0cd"}}, "hash": "aeee1a00089474614ea2560f36c777ed09447ee65b85945a169c303e51c5a16f", "text": "in services experienced annually. 4.1 Services trade and FDI in services in Asia In 1990, the services sector contributed more than 60 percent of GDP in most of the industrialized countries while in the developing countries of Asia it ranged between 40 to 45 percent in 1990 (Karthikeyan 2007). Much has changed since then with a Pricewaterhouse Coopers survey in 2006 suggesting that two major Asian economies, China and India, are the two most attractive locations for FDI in emerging markets (WIR 2006). In recent years, the trend in services trade has been that of its concentration in some Asian developing countries. In 2003, 12 leading exporters of services among developing countries accounted for 71 percent of services export of all developing countries. The group of leading services exporters from the developing world included Asian countries like China, India, Republic of Korea, Malaysia and Thailand (UNCTAD 2005:3). Singapore and Hong Kong (SAR, China) are the other countries from Asia which have become major service providers. Table 3 shows the manner in which export and import of services in Asian countries has risen over the period 1980 - 2006. 13 Table 3: Change in value of exports and imports of services Country 1980 1990 2000 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 China - 5855 30431 39745 46734 62434 74404 (e)86376 Hong Kong (SAR, China) - - 40430 44601 46555 55157 62175 (e)69059 Republic of Korea 2570 9637 30534 28388 32957 41882 45375 51874 Mongolia - 48 78 184 208 338 (e)414 (e)447 Bangladesh 211 392 815 849 1012 1083 1245 1296 India 2971 4625 16684 19478 23397 (e)292