policy space measures in select Asian countries 15 5.1 Understanding the nature of commitments 5.1.1 Horizontal commitments Contrary to sectoral commitments, the list of horizontal commitments applies to all sectors covered in the schedule. They work as a negative threshold - no horizontal commitment implies that no restrictions other than those listed in the schedules apply. Countries without any indication of horizontal commitments have chosen not to impose any general limitation and, therefore, their restrictions and qualifications are confined to those listed in the sectoral schedules for the sectors included. Horizontal commitments do not cover sectors that have not been subject to sectoral commitments. In other words, a sector that is not included in the schedule is not subject to any commitment, regardless of what is listed as a horizontal commitment.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c93299c6-2928-44b2-aa1d-5e3eb3a4f8f6": {"__data__": {"id_": "c93299c6-2928-44b2-aa1d-5e3eb3a4f8f6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5a6a7bc915b694bafbfad36fc92db84856830cb50f57e697b19dee68bfbe0c92"}, "2": {"node_id": "c6ed2f28-7505-43f2-bf18-27b57cd94a86", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aeee1a00089474614ea2560f36c777ed09447ee65b85945a169c303e51c5a16f"}}, "hash": "57df26ded1927372b2b90b2f230d79892aea4aaac93d2e72f247f49615f6a0cd", "text": "This scheduling system is called \u201cpositive listing\u201d. Of the 14 countries studied, the following three did not include any horizontal restrictions: Bangladesh, Mongolia and the Kyrgyz Republic. Horizontal commitments need to be taken into account in order to assess the extension", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "29931432-fb50-40f6-ac74-581797593dad": {"__data__": {"id_": "29931432-fb50-40f6-ac74-581797593dad", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9abd6086dfffd15399175ba6454ee9b623aef7dd9865574f221245e617935f2e"}, "3": {"node_id": "6a1e5188-ae73-4314-96d4-f75c412e5ccd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a972ca70199e16c20c5f14c162d27b27b560e0e94e1a4a3dbd571432964bc6a8"}}, "hash": "0d7cffe19ed7552657ac1b5747f2c9bb00fa692d84ffc17d6f4e71fe047c3cab", "text": "of liberalization at the sectoral level, as such commitments protect the overall policy space. Normally, sectoral commitments are more restrictive than those that are made horizontally, for any given sec- tor. If that is not the case, the extension of liberalization would have to be expressly stated in the schedule. Horizontal restrictions in MA or pre-establishment conditions are mostly control and ownership limita- tions. NT commitments are more common at the horizontal level. The majority of countries included land ownership limitations. Most countries also included other types of NT restrictions, such as on technology transfer and training requirements, but more often, on subsidies and incentives. 5.1.2 MA commitments Under GATS, member countries have been provided with an option to allow the entry of foreign services providers (exporters) under a predetermined set of conditions for accessing the markets of the importing countries. As has been discussed in the introduction, MA under services is a much more complex area than under goods, as it relates to the area of government regulation/policies which are generally aimed at attain- ment of domestic policy objectives and not trade policy per se. Scheduling market access limitations is hence critical in exercise of policy space. Each sectoral commitment has two columns where countries fill in the measures they apply in terms of: \uf06c MA: Under GATS, there are six types of MA measures, listed in Article XVI, which can be summarized as quantitative restrictions (QRs), limitations in the type of legal entity or joint venture and limitations on foreign-equity participation. The latter refers to the limits on the extent of foreign capital in the sectors that are scheduled, as conditions for establishment. \uf06c NT: This, according to Article XVII, refers to any discriminatory measure other than the conditions or qualifications set out in the country schedules that may serve to modify the conditions of competition against foreign service providers. Countries may schedule measures relating to both MA and NT. In cases where the measures are not covered under both MA and NT, the same needs to be inscribed, according to Article XX.2, in the MA column. This explains the larger variety of measures covering MA, as well as the larger number of other measures found listed in the MA column of country schedules. Illustratively, the types of restrictions found in the MA column are listed below: 16 \uf06c Economic needs tests (ENTs) \uf06c Environmental, cultural, and historical concerns \uf06c Experience/certification/rating/size of investor41 \uf06c Joint venture (JV)/foreign-equity ceiling42 \uf06c Foreign-equity ceilings \uf06c National board members43 \uf06c Licensing/number of service providers44 \uf06c Prudential risk management45 \uf06c Residence/nationality requirements \uf06c Forms of establishment \uf06c Need for local agent \uf06c Limits on business scope \uf06c Geographic limitations \uf06c Import limits \uf06c Unbound It is possible to find, in each sectoral commitment, one or more restrictions\u2014for example, a licensing requirement along with a geographic limitation and a foreign-equity ceiling. In such cases, each restriction is taken as an individual annotation or record. However, some types of restrictions are incompatible as they have the same direct implications\u2014for example, a licensing requirement and an ENT or a joint venture requirement and a limitation in the form of establishment. 5.1.3 Full Commitments Full commitments in MA are represented by a \u2018none\u2019 entry beside the scheduled sector. A \u2018none\u2019 entry es- sentially implies that the country has not exercised its right to apply any MA restriction or conditions on the delivery of services in its territory by a foreign services supplier. Members intending to build in developmental policies and wishing to keep them in place need to list them in their schedule only if these policies constitute a barrier or discrimination against foreign suppliers. However, countries need to take a dynamic and futuristic view of and in this sense it should be clear that the same development objective might require the application of different policies and, therefore, MA restrictions in different periods of time. A full commitment will impede that possibility in the future. In sectoral terms, most full commitments have been made in business services, tourism and construction. 5.2 Use of MA measures In order to facilitate the understanding of the schedules, the variety of possible measures can be grouped into four types: 1. Control limitations: foreign-equity ceilings; joint-venture requirements/equity ceilings; and national board members\u2019 requirements.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6a1e5188-ae73-4314-96d4-f75c412e5ccd": {"__data__": {"id_": "6a1e5188-ae73-4314-96d4-f75c412e5ccd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publicatio