olicy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "63b7ada928be8a99cab3979f4965cae700d7d48d751003b572a8880ff03d8ffa"}, "3": {"node_id": "c69c52dd-ab85-4c84-abfb-cca22a92c416", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "829a58ead3095f0dadad4e52be4c4719491626b332de2c6f98515c9623fa1d22"}}, "hash": "74779b2de66477cd5487c7abdd5752fc178e529f58dd7cef4800ab5d1a25a24d", "text": "This type of restriction has a similar objective as limitations in foreign equity, often appearing together to maintain control over the company and reduce risks. 44 Although licensing requirements are initially covered by the Domestic Regulation disciplines of Article 6.4 of GATS and, therefore, are not MA restrictions, the criteria applied during the licensing process may contain a MA restriction, or the license may be granted in a discretionary manner, with the same effects as a QR. 45 See UNCTAD (2006). 17 2. Quantitative limitations: licensing/number of service providers; experience/certification/rating/size of investor; residence/nationality requirements; market share in foreign hands; import limits; and pruden- tial risk management. 3. Forms of establishment: forms of establishment; joint-venture requirements; joint venture/foreign- equity ceilings; limits on business scope; need of local agent; and geographic limitations. 4. ENTs and environmental, cultural and historical concerns.46 5.2.1 MA restrictions: Control limitations Control limitations, while allowing foreign ownership up to a certain threshold, tend to limit the capacity of the foreign investor to control the corporations in a specific sub-sector. Such restrictions normally target strategic planning and policy making at the corporate level, focusing on the types of decisions that are taken by the board of directors. The sectors targeted by control limitations are business services, construction, communications, finance, health and tourism. Unless specified in the schedule, other types of arrangements such as manage- ment and exploitation contracts, build operate transfer (BOT) schemes, etc., involving foreign enterprises, are not covered by these restrictions. Control limitations are, by far, the most frequent. Moreover, various types of control limitation restric- tions normally appear together; yet national board members requirements are to be found only with another type of control limitation restriction. China, India, Nepal, the Philippines and Thailand are the main users of control and ownership limi- tations. Thailand includes a foreign-equity participation limitation across the board. Indonesia, Republic of Korea, Pakistan and the Philippines have also introduced restrictions horizontally. However, China, India, Nepal, the Philippines and Thailand are seen to apply these measures in differ- ent ways. First, the scheduled foreign-equity ceilings vary greatly among them: 1. The Philippines and Thailand have limited foreign control and even limited the number of nationals on the boards of directors of corporate entities. These countries also have horizontal commitments that affect foreign control, so the ceilings on foreign ownership are lower at the sectoral level. 2. China and India have generally committed to foreign control stakes (51 percent in India, and fully foreign owned in China), except in the telecom and transport sectors. 3. Nepal allows foreign control stakes across the board, with foreign-equity ceilings up to 80 percent. The cases of China and Nepal are of great interest. Both scheduled progressive phase-outs, of up to eight years, so as to allow increasing ownership of foreign firms in their services sectors. Both countries have committed themselves to allow foreign investors to control the companies invested in by them. However, China\u2019s commitments also include the need for joint ventures with a local partner. Nepal, on the other hand, requires local incorporation (with a local partner in control of a very small part of the capital). This type of schedule has been used previously\u2014around the beginning of the current decade\u2014by India for selected sec- tors in its schedule (business services, construction, health and tourism). In the case of China and Nepal, the objective of the commitments is not to retain control of the sector, but to encourage foreign entry and control, not through acquisition of existing businesses, but through creat- ing new businesses (promoting greenfield investment), enabling the creation of partnerships with the local businesses, and, possibly, increasing technology transfer to the local partner. 46 ENTs, by definition, is a quantitative limitation. However, these were grouped separately as they may also imply a variety of measures. Often, they are also defined by an explicit development objective. They may also appear along with other quantitative measures, a direct proof of their separate nature. 18 In contrast, India, Philippines and Thailand do not allow incorporation of new foreign businesses. Foreign-equity limits must then apply to financial operations so as to enable raising of capital for the develop- ment of existing local companies, as was the norm at the time when privatization first occurred in key services sectors.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c69c52dd-ab85-4c84-abfb-cca22a92c416": {"__data__": {"id_": "c69c52dd-ab85-4c84-abfb-cca22a92c416", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "63b7ada928be8a99cab3979f4965cae700d7d48d751003b572a8880ff03d8ffa"}, "2": {"node_id": "9f3650de-d0d9-493d-9180-e6f3307cda30", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "74779b2de66477cd5487c7abdd5752fc178e529f58dd7cef4800ab5d1a25a24d"}}, "hash": "829a58ead3095f0dadad4e52be4c4719491626b332de2c6f98515c9623fa1d22", "text": "5.2.2 MA restrictions: Quantitative limitations\u2014reducing competition and risks All Asian countries included such measures when scheduling their telecom, banking, insurance and other financial services sub-sectors, which are prominent in the schedules and are subject to the largest number of restrictions as compared to other sub-sectors. However, the use and prominence of these kinds of restrictions varies among these", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "edd7e9a6-fcd6-4af9-877f-88f3ceab0d4e": {"__data__": {"id_": "edd7e9a6-fcd6-4af9-877f-88f3ceab0d4e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f94c49038bbb91dc6909bfca74283cdd6c8b981e2a08a3c455f8c01c533a1f5d"}}, "hash": "f94c49038bbb91dc6909bfca74283cdd6c8b981e2a08a3c455f8c01c533a1f5d", "text": "four sub-sectors: 1. In the telecommunications sector, all the registered restrictions are intended to limit the number of service providers that can compete in the market (licensing). Licensing is widely used in the telecom- munications sub-sector, in order to ensure the profitability of the competitors. 2. In the financial sector, the objective seems to be security and risk avoidance. This may explain why licens- ing restrictions accompany other measures relating to the certification of the quality, experience and reliability of the service provider. Some measures that help to avoid balance-of-payment risks also are included. In other sectors, these types of measures are used marginally, mostly to ensure that the new entrants will make a difference in terms of the projects involved and their engagement in the local economy. 5.2.3 MA restrictions: Limitations in the forms of establishment This category of restrictions includes those measures that limit the capacity of the foreign juridical person to decide, in a particular country: \uf06c The type of legal entity, and, therefore, legal capacity of the subsidiary; and \uf06c The scope of commercial activity. This limitation can apply to the type of service or client, amount of the contracts and geographic area of activity. Therefore, entry is allowed, but these types of limitations will define the basic features of the busi- ness model in a given country, otherwise decided by the shareholders of the entity. The variety of forms and purposes of these limitations are very wide. By their substantial features, the limitations can be divided into two groups: \uf06c Those that impose a specific type of legal entity: limitations in the forms of establishment, JV require- ments (with and without foreign-equity ceilings) and need for a local agent. These measures are incom- patible (that is, they cannot appear at the same time). \uf06c Those that limit the foreign investors\u2019 market operations: business scope and geographic limitations. Limitations on business scope normally forbid the foreign investor from engaging in the provision of certain services within the sector (by contract volume, type of buyer, etc.). Geographic limitations are mostly applied through a limit on the number of branches in the local market, which, by itself, constrains the geographic scope. 19 These types of restrictions have been used by a limited number of countries in the case of limitations in the form of establishment. On the other hand, Indonesia and the Republic of Korea impose horizontal restrictions in the form of commercial presence: \uf06c Indonesia requires that any kind of foreign commercial presence should be in the form of a representa- tive office or a joint venture with a foreign equity ceiling of 49 percent. \uf06c The Republic of Korea restricts foreign commercial presence through the acquisition of outstanding stocks of existing domestic companies, which basically leads to the need for setting up new business facilities towards incorporation of any commercial interest in the country. Therefore, these countries have shown preference for forms of establishment that imply greenfield investment which if channelled appropriately can have beneficial employment linkages in the host economy. Though they tend to be used across the board, the preferred sectors are professional services, banking, insur- ance, construction, maritime transport and audiovisual services. However, a further analysis of the composi- tion of restrictions by sub-sectors reveals a marked preference for limitations in the form of establishment for professional services, while limitations on business scope and geographic limitations are mostly used in banking and insurance. In the case of professional services, limitations in the form of establishment are normally used to limit the ability of the foreign service provider to penetrate the market. The limitations may imply that only natu- ral persons, partnerships and other non-limited liability companies, with limited resources, can access the market. These types of limitations, combined with restrictions under Mode 4 horizontal commitments can significantly reduce MA, particularly when combined with a nationality/residence requirement. With regard to banking and insurance, limitations in the form of establishment will only allow repre- sentations and agencies, and, in many cases, limited number of branches and limited scope of businesses. The obligation to use a local agent will produce a similar effect. This situation is common in the schedule of the Republic of Korea when targeting specific sectors in which full foreign participation, even through greenfield investment, is not welcome. This is the reason for a more mixed composition of restrictions in the banking and insurance sub-sectors, compared to professional services. 5.2.4 ENT: Another way of limiting MA ENTs can appear in various forms. They limit the number of service suppliers, and imply a variety of measures with an indefinite impact. Often, they", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6ec879cf-783e-4347-84ce-8a24a904e0a2": {"__data__": {"id_": "6ec879cf-783e-4347-84ce-8a24a904e0a2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c32e0cd1dbd98846e116da2e451bf42e1c435bb43d376db656a8409a4880a835"}}, "hash": "c32e0cd1dbd98846e116da2e451bf42e1c435bb43d376db656a8409a4880a835", "text": "refer to specific development objectives. At the same time, they seem to be the most restrictive, as they restrain access to the market under generally unspecified or discretionary criteria. Within the services sector, they are mostly used to regulate the entry of natural persons as service providers, but are also to be found covering a range of specific activities. 5.3 Trends in the use of MA restrictions From an examination of the main types of MA restrictions used by countries, it can be seen that independently of the number of sectors scheduled, there is a tendency towards less usage of control and ownership mea- sures. This conclusion is based on the fact that apart from the LDCs, the prevalence of control measures is very limited in Cambodia, China, Hong Kong (SAR, China) and Singapore. In the case of Nepal, as mentioned earlier, foreign-equity ceilings are not used with the main purpose of retaining local control. It seems that control measures have been targeted to serve as the main constraints for foreign participation. On the other hand, 20 full MA commitments are more common among NACs. In these cases, developing countries will not be able to use restrictions to limit the ability of foreign investors to penetrate their markets. However, the possible negative impact of this trend can be offset by the use of other types of limitations which while granting MA in principle, shape the way in which the foreign company engages in the local economy. These are basically limitations in the form of establishment and in business scope. As compared to limitations on control and ownership, limitations in the form of establishment may have a more positive effect insofar as they can promote greenfield investment and competition and tech- nology transfer, more flexibly, than control limitations. Other practices can have the same final effect. For example, the need for local incorporation would, in effect, ban the acquisition of local companies. The decision on an appropriate context specific combination of measures relating to the form of estab- lishment which integrates the best interests of both investors and local communities is a strategic judgement and often complex one to make. For example, in hotel services, granting full ownership would not in itself attract foreign suppliers if other, more preferred forms of engagement, such as management contracts, are not allowed. Joint venture requirements may not work as a stimulus for technology transfer if the local partner is unable to absorb foreign technology, and in fact, may deter the provision of key services to the rest of the economy. Limitations in business scope can induce foreign investors to fill in a market niche as part of a com- prehensive industrial development strategy. They also can be used to avoid crowding out local companies from a specific segment, as, for example, in the case of Cambodia, which allows foreign-owned hotels only if they are rated three star or higher. 5.4 NT commitments The principle of NT is an obligation intended to ensure that the member country does not discriminate be- tween the foreign service suppliers of the member countries and the domestic service suppliers. It is not across the board obligation, and members are free to choose both specific sectors, and also lay down specific conditions and qualifications under which NT would be provided to suit their own national development policy objectives and context and state of development of their services sector. In other words, both in terms of the sectoral coverage and substantive content, members have the policy space under GATs to choose their NT obligations and commitments. Under NT, for all the sectors inscribed in its Schedule and subject to the conditions and qualifications set out therein, each member is obliged to accord to services and service suppliers of any other member, in respect of all measures affecting the supply of services, treatment no less favourable than that it accords to its own like services and service suppliers. In order to meet this requirement, a member can provide formally identical treatment or formally different treatment to that it accords to its own services and service suppliers. The main idea is that in either case, the treatment would be considered less favourable if it serves to modify the conditions of competition in favour of services or service suppliers of any other member. The GATS also has a list of General Exceptions (Article XIV) wherein members are permitted to exercise in contravention of the Agreement subject to the fact that the measures do not constitute arbitrary or unjusti- fiable discrimination between countries where like conditions prevail or seen as a form of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b49a1f3b-7d69-4841-8289-6c75fc05d0d4": {"__data__": {"id_": "b49a1f3b-7d69-4841-8289-6c75fc05d0d4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a23b4c7e8fbe35fde845a1905d614092a5cf17792e88d1cb575f7b79de0f9111"}, "3": {"node_id": "d4026b47-610a-4cf5-b032-ff69b360bc1a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "309d90c268aec009d01524b791a034c03f5e9e066fa5269e1565b2bf4d2b152a"}}, "hash": "364b5a5ddab899941c6977fc486946f6ef365a77d2a390635bf5c2ae1ed56fb1", "text": "disguised restriction on trade in services. These exceptions can be on the grounds of protecting public morals to maintain public order; protect human, animal or plant life or health; prevent deceptive and fraudulent practices; protection of the privacy of individuals in relation to the processing and dissemination of personal data; and so on. NT restrictions are used by all countries across the sectors, but more specifically in communications, finance and maritime transport. The NT restriction scheduled by the countries relate to: 21 \uf06c Employment requirements \uf06c Export requirements \uf06c Higher paid-up capital \uf06c Higher quality standards \uf06c Land ownership \uf06c Local content \uf06c Research and development (R&D) subsidies/incentives \uf06c Registration fee requirement \uf06c Subsidies \uf06c Tax breaks and incentives \uf06c Technology/training requirements \uf06c Transparency requirements \uf06c Unbound As can be seen from this list, development objectives are clear in most of the measures\u2014employment, quality, land ownership, R&D, technology and training requirements, accountability requirements, etc. Performance requirements, in a variety of forms (local content, import restrictions, technology/ training requirements, etc.) have been used by China and Indonesia. Cambodia, India, and Sri Lanka include performance requirements (training requirements) horizontally. Subsidies and incentives exceptions were used by Bangladesh and Hong Kong (SAR, China), while Cambodia, China, Republic of Korea and Nepal introduced them in their horizontal commitments. Land ownership restrictions were scheduled at the horizontal level by many countries. However, limitations in land ownership do not mean limitations in land use. The sectoral schedules show the wide variety of policies used by developing countries in the region in order to achieve specific developmental objectives. 5.5 Most Favoured Nation exemptions The principle of MFN constitutes a general obligation by the member state to extend the most favourable treatment affecting trade in services accorded to any of its trading partner\u2019s to all the other members im- mediately and unconditionally. The provision laid down under Article II of GATS serves to ensure that it\u2019s not less favourable than what is accorded to other member states. The basic principle of the Agreement is that specific commitments are applied on an MFN basis. Measures inconsistent with the MFN obligation can be maintained subject to reviews after every five years in principle up to a period of 10 years at the entry into force of the GATS. Any subsequent exemption to MFN can only be granted under the waiver rules laid down in the WTO Agreement. MFN exemptions are also to be a subject matter of negotiations in the current and future rounds of trade negotiations. Preferential treatment to members of free trade agreements are however, permitted under Article V of GATS with some criteria such as having substantial sectoral coverage laid down, and it is not necessary for any country to list them out in their GATS schedule. Asian countries have only targeted a limited number of sectors and sub-sectors (audiovisual services, banking, construction and related engineering services, cultural and sporting services, maritime transport, telecommunication services, road transport and recreational services). Within these, audiovisual services, banking, maritime transport and telecom account for most of the MFN \u201csectoral\u201d exemptions. Considering the types of benefits that would accrue to members, in more than half of the records, countries are likely to ease MA requirements. The rest of the exemptions either provide for NT in terms of rates and fees applied to foreign telecom and maritime companies or NT in terms of subsidies and incentives for foreign companies working in audiovisual services under co-production arrangements. 22 This section provides a succinct analysis of the impact that GATS has on the flexibilities of countries to exercise policy space to enhance the qualitative and quantitative growth of their services sector in the larger macro- economic context. Countries that satisfy both the attributes listed below are a part of such analysis: \uf06c Services sector should be contributing in the range of 30 percent to 55 percent of GDP (this is to ensure that service-dominated economies such as Singapore, Hong Kong (SAR, China) and Jordan do not distort the picture). \uf06c The ratio of trade in services to GDP should not be higher than 25 percent. The sample therefore consists of the following countries: Bangladesh, Cambodia, China, India, Indone- sia, Republic of Korea, Kyrgyz Republic, Nepal, Pakistan, the Philippines, Sri Lanka and Thailand.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d4026b47-610a-4cf5-b032-ff69b360bc1a": {"__data__": {"id_": "d4026b47-610a-4cf5-b032-ff69b360bc1a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a23b4c7e8fbe35fde845a1905d614092a5cf17792e88d1cb575f7b79de0f9111"}, "2": {"node_id": "b49a1f3b-7d69-4841-8289-6c75fc05d0d4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "364b5a5ddab899941c6977fc486946f6ef365a77d2a390635bf5c2ae1ed56fb1"}}, "hash": "309d90c268aec009d01524b791a034c03f5e9e066fa5269e1565b2bf4d2b152a", "text": "Annex 1 contains a brief description of the Mode 3 commitments made by countries that have been included in the sample above. 6. Bangladesh 6.1.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments Bangladesh has scheduled commitments in only two services sectors (communication and tourism). It thus ranks lowest among the group of sampled Asian countries in terms of the number of services", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e698f6ca-9699-48a4-81ce-9e48273ede64": {"__data__": {"id_": "e698f6ca-9699-48a4-81ce-9e48273ede64", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "143784e2f7d1495b805fb214c279577bd30ff820915bb5fcdafae876e52aa31d"}}, "hash": "143784e2f7d1495b805fb214c279577bd30ff820915bb5fcdafae876e52aa31d", "text": "sectors committed by it. \uf06c Communications: The telecommunication services sector is scheduled with the government operator having an exclusive right to supply international telecommunication services of public use, like voice telephony, telex and telegraph service etc. For domestic long distance and local service, two private operators are to be issued licenses to serve designated rural areas in competition with the government operator. For provision of mobile services, only four private operators are to be issued licenses in addi- tion to the government operator. Bangladesh has also reserved Very Small Aperture Terminal (VSAT) satellite services for exclusive supply by the government operator. These commitments clearly show that Bangladesh has been conservative with respect to making com- mitments on the telecom sector. \uf06c Tourism and travel related services: Bangladesh has made commitments only with respect to estab- lishment of hotels in this sector. It requires that all foreign investors who set up hotels in the country incorporate their business in Bangladesh in accordance with local laws. Foreign equity to the extent of 100 percent is allowed in setting up of hotels. 6. Analysis of schedules of commitments: broad trends in use of policy space flexibilities 23 6.1.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Telecommunications Bangladesh\u2019s telecommunications sector was monopolized by the Bangladesh Telegraph and Telephone Board (BTTB), under the Ministry of Post and Telecommunications, till 1989. In recent times, the government has significantly reduced its role in the telecommunications sector and removed restrictions on FDI therein. The Bangladesh Telecommunication Act 2001, as well as the Telecommunication Policy of 1998, seeks to encourage foreign investment in the telecom sector. Six private firms47, each of which includes foreign investors, are licensed to provide cellular phone services in Bangladesh. Other telecommunication services also no longer have government monopoly. The large unmet demand for telephone lines has resulted in this sector having a very large potential for expansion. Telecommunications services are expected to attract considerable investment from both large and small investors. In 2002, the telecom sector grabbed 23 percent of all FDI, while rest of the services shared 4 percent of the pie. However, expansion in the sector is still constrained by the ability of the BTTB to provide the necessary inter-connectivity. Financial services The Trade Policy Review (TPR) (2006) for Bangladesh notes that foreign banks are encouraged to take a role in the provision of banking services given the lack of funds for development in the country. They are allowed to conduct the same business as local banks. However, in order to operate a branch, foreign banks are required to obtain a license from the Bangladesh Bank (BB), the central bank of the country, which is given only if there is reciprocity between the foreign bank\u2019s home country and Bangladesh. Insurance business is also open to private investment since 1984. However, till 2006, the American Life Insurance Company (ALICO) was the only foreign insurance company operating in Bangladesh. Other sectors In air transport, since late 1996, the private sector has been allowed to compete with the state airline on all domestic passenger routes and on national and international cargo routes. Domestic routes are reserved for the national airlines. In 2005-06, about 18 foreign and two national airlines offered scheduled passenger services to and from Bangladesh, while non-scheduled cargo services were carried out by eight international and domestic operators. International air traffic from Bangladesh is growing at around six-seven percent a year. The state-owned airline \u2018Biman\u2019 and international airlines operate 75 and 100 weekly international flights, respectively. However, despite the move towards liberalization, six foreign airlines decided to cease their operations in Bangladesh. 6.1.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services accounting for 52.4 percent of Bangladeshi GDP (World Bank 2007) are critical in defining the growth path of its GDP. Wholesale and retail trade; transport, storage and communications, community, social and personal services; and real estate and business services continue to be the important service sectors in Ban- gladesh. The services sector employs about a third of the labour force (mainly in trade, hotel and restaurant services). 47 List of cellular mobile phone operators are available on the official website of the Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission (BTRC). 24 The quantum and quality of commitments made by Bangladesh at the WTO in comparison to the autonomous commitments made by it in the same sectors and across various other sectors does not suggest that Bangladesh has abdicated its policy space, while liberalizing its services sector under GATS. Moreover, Bangladesh has also not made any offers as a part of the GATS (2000) negotiations. In the context of Bangladesh, gross domestic investments as a percentage", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "31505006-665e-4afc-89cb-28bfb671fc03": {"__data__": {"id_": "31505006-665e-4afc-89cb-28bfb671fc03", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "31e28e646e6b356b47c019be0fd25caf300a96c22491d0df873b2d16b12b5d36"}}, "hash": "31e28e646e6b356b47c019be0fd25caf300a96c22491d0df873b2d16b12b5d36", "text": "of GDP have been consis- tently higher in comparison to the gross domestic savings as a percentage of GDP over the last two decades. During the year 2006, gross domestic investment as a percentage of GDP exceeded gross domestic savings as a percentage of GDP by approximately five percentage points. This shows that foreign investment is critical in complementing the gaps that are left uncovered by domestic savings into the investment space. Around one third of the total employment in Bangladesh is dependent on services (Muqtada 2003). In spite of efforts made in the area of manufacturing, employment opportunities in the manufacturing sector of Bangladesh have not risen. Moreover given the dependence of local manufacturing on exports, labour is increasingly being displaced by technology in Bangladesh to ensure export competitiveness. Services, which constitute a lion\u2019s share of economy, therefore need to grow at a pace that can absorb the growing literate Bangladeshi population to avoid brain drain. Shortage of investible capital in the services sector, therefore, has emerged as a concern. A strategic opening up to foreign investment inflows in areas that can create scale effects and trigger employment in downstream and upstream sectors is a possible policy option. As far as commitments under GATS are con- cerned, Bangladesh has shown a preference for retention of policy space and a tailoring of the schedules to its development context. There is a lack of services related trade data in Bangladesh and thus a proper assessment of risks and benefits needs to be undertaken before liberalizing other individual sub sectors in Bangladesh. 6.2 Cambodia 6.2.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments Cambodia has scheduled commitments for eleven sectors. \uf06c Accounting, consulting and tax services: Cambodia provides MA and NT to foreign firms providing ac- counting, auditing and taxation services. \uf06c Legal services: According to the Cambodian Law on the Bar adopted in 1995, foreign lawyers cannot rep- resent clients, conduct activities to attract clients or publish commercial advertisements. However, they are permitted to work in commercial association with Cambodian lawyers. The commercial association requirement does not apply when legal services are provided in the area of foreign and international law. \uf06c Architectural and engineering services: Cross-border supply for architectural services is not restricted and NT is granted. Foreign citizens can provide engineering and integrated engineering services. \uf06c Telecommunications services: For the most part, access to Cambodia\u2019s telecommunications services market is not restricted. Private participation in mobile services, e-mail, electronic data interchange and code and protocol conversion is allowed and NT is accorded. In addition, Cambodia is committed to permitting licensed suppliers of mobile communications services to choose which technology to use for such services. Cross-border supply for voice telephone services, circuit-switched data transmission and private leased circuit services are allowed only over circuits leased from Telecom Cambodia, a public sector entity. This restriction will be eliminated by January 2009, and foreign participation of up to 49 percent equity will be allowed. Cambodia is making preparations to create an independent regulatory body. 25 \uf06c Audiovisual services: Cambodia does not prohibit foreign firms from distributing foreign films and vid- eotapes. \uf06c Distribution services: No limitation on MA or NT is imposed on foreign firms wishing to engage in distri- bution services; i.e., wholesale trade and retailing services. Like other business activities, foreign firms are required to register with the Ministry of Commerce to obtain a business license. \uf06c Educational services: Foreign participation in educational services is not restricted. \uf06c Insurance services: Licensed insurance companies including foreign companies can provide all types of insurance products. Cambodia\u2019s insurance sector is governed by the Law on Insurance of 2000. \uf06c Banking services: Cambodia allows foreign firms to operate as either 100 percent owned subsidiaries or as branches. The 1999 Law on Banking and Financial Institutions and subsequent regulations guarantee foreign banks rights and obligations equal to local banks. The law imposes no restrictions on foreign ownership of banks. \uf06c Health-related services: Cambodia permits cross-border investment in hospital services. For commercial presence, foreign ownership and management of private hospitals and clinics is permitted as long as at least one director, for technical matters, is Cambodian. Foreign firms are allowed to provide dental services through joint ventures with Cambodian legal entities. \uf06c Tourism and travel related services: Cambodia does not restrict foreigners\u2019 participation in this sector. Foreign companies may establish a commercial presence to operate hotels, restaurants, travel agencies and tour operator services, provided they register with the Ministry of Commerce for business licenses. Except for a few strategic sectors (transport and telecommunications), Cambodia has eliminated re- strictions for MA. However, in some sectors of interest, such as", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4505e62e-eedc-4d46-b6a3-0b8e6ce6c39f": {"__data__": {"id_": "4505e62e-eedc-4d46-b6a3-0b8e6ce6c39f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e7732a1866ea4ad84be8f664e33ece2b13f8d6a7000e376932ee13f53a1d8326"}, "3": {"node_id": "bbb87f1e-7b4d-4c53-89a7-1c325efab9bf", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "333b7e7502012af5ac998a5757cad0df783978f19d835dce664d23ae0c4e85d2"}}, "hash": "9909e08988c909c6a1b7892dbe21c564b815b4b61b623e919707ead4e93e3a16", "text": "health, finance and tourism, some conditions apply so as to ensure that market penetration does not jeopardize specific public goals in terms of environ- mental and consumer protection, without reducing market opportunities to foreign investors. NT limitations are mostly scheduled horizontally, with a strong emphasis on technology and skills transfer, and subsidies are restricted to nationals, which provide some room for industrial policy development. 6.2.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Cambodia\u2019s legislation regarding the services sector has generally complied with the principles and provisions of the GATS.48 Cambodia provides MA or NT for commercial presence of almost all services, and is believed to have potential for attracting foreign investment in most of its services sectors. The Cambodian government actively solicits foreign private investment to boost its economic devel- opment. At the autonomous liberalization level, Cambodia\u2019s 1994 Investment Law, amended in 2003, accords NT to all foreign investors. However, the Cambodian Constitution restricts foreign ownership of land. Foreign investors may use land through concessions, unlimited long-term land leases and renewable limited short- term leases. 48 Visit http://phnompenh.usembassy.gov/uploads/images/nccimQfzXrVvgejbz8lziw/Nat_Trade_Est.pdf, accessed 25 September 2007. 26 6.2.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS According to the World Bank, services contributed around 39.1 percent to the GDP of Cambodia during 2005. Important components of the services sector in Cambodia are trade, transport, communications, tourism, real estate and business services. Cambodian economy is gradually diversifying and, like Bangladesh, Cambodia is also seen to be lack- ing domestic capital and technical expertise that can help it to diversify rapidly and efficiently in services sectors. Tourism is the key service sector of Cambodia contributing for more than two-thirds of its services sector revenue. Cambodian administration has taken active steps to liberalize commercial presence of foreign entities in its tourism sector by not only making commitments at an autonomous level but also under GATS. It is important to note that Cambodia and Nepal were amongst the first LDCs to join the WTO since its creation in 1995.49 The accession process spanning nine years was not informed by any comprehensive re- search or public debate on the costs and benefits of joining the WTO. There was ignorance, at large, amongst the civil society and the country\u2019s parliamentarians about the substance of negotiations.50 Analysts have noted that in the process of accession, Cambodia was pressurized by WTO members to make concessions that are far deeper than the levels of commitments made by LDCs which are already members of the WTO.51 The idea, perhaps, was to create an ambitious template for future members seeking to accede to the WTO. The GATS commitments as discussed previously are in line with the ambitious MA commitments un- dertaken by the country. Cambodia has made deep MA commitments under GATS and aligned its domestic legislations to comply with its GATS commitments. Cambodia has not made any offers as part of the GATS (2000) negotiations. While a deeper analysis of the human development implications is beyond the scope of this paper, it can be said that the nature of commitments in the schedules even in critical sectors providing public goods like health and education, indicate that the country has had to surrender its policy space to meet the WTO accession requirements. 6.3 Peoples\u2019 Republic of China 6.3.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments China has made heterogeneous and specific commitments in nine sectors (business services; communication services; construction and related engineering services; distribution services; educational services; environ- mental services; financial services; tourism and travel related services; and transport services) which are dif- ficult to summarize, as in the case of other countries. In its horizontal commitments schedule, MA limitations with regard to commercial presence include minimum equity requirements on MA for foreign equity held in a joint venture (at least 25 percent of the reg- istered capital of the joint venture). The establishment of branches by foreign enterprises is unbound unless otherwise indicated in the specific commitments; representative offices of foreign enterprises are permitted to establish in China, but may not engage in any profit making activities, except as indicated in China\u2019s specific commitments.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bbb87f1e-7b4d-4c53-89a7-1c325efab9bf": {"__data__": {"id_": "bbb87f1e-7b4d-4c53-89a7-1c325efab9bf", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e7732a1866ea4ad84be8f664e33ece2b13f8d6a7000e376932ee13f53a1d8326"}, "2": {"node_id": "4505e62e-eedc-4d46-b6a3-0b8e6ce6c39f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9909e08988c909c6a1b7892dbe21c564b815b4b61b623e919707ead4e93e3a16"}}, "hash": "333b7e7502012af5ac998a5757cad0df783978f19d835dce664d23ae0c4e85d2", "text": "There are also limitations with regard to ownership of land by enterprises and individuals: 70 years for residential purposes; 50 years for industrial, education, science, culture, public health, physical education and \u201ccomprehensive utilization\u201d (multi-utilization of land, according to the authorities) and other 49 Visit http://www.wto.org/english/res_e/booksp_e/casestudies_e/case8_e.htm, accessed 27 November 2007. 50 Ibid. 51 Visit http://www.phnompenhpost.com/TXT/comments/c1219-1.htm, accessed 27 November 2007. 27 purposes; and 40 years for commercial, tourism and recreational purposes. In educational services sector, China has allowed for establishment of joint schools with foreign majority ownership permitted. It is also significant to note", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b3e7e3cf-f1c8-40f0-bd5c-4c9457f042c9": {"__data__": {"id_": "b3e7e3cf-f1c8-40f0-bd5c-4c9457f042c9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "acda751fc4ef63227cef479b293f6f4996c5939c5123b899ae607d5adea120b8"}, "3": {"node_id": "b99d9668-83a5-493a-9dac-00f82d805d61", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "624539026b148c1bcf3dc7bd638a7ba863794c3194cc0b7841f72b5f89154951"}}, "hash": "ef56cc7844ed9bb11af86500dc921f2c95705cd8ae62e5ba3b6166365de900c5", "text": "that China has kept restrictions on NT in health (with an employment re- quirement) and air transport, though it eliminated other forms of discrimination for the rest of the sectors. China has committed to an extensive liberalization of its services sectors, with notable exceptions (con- struction, recreational services, research and development services, telecommunications, travel agency ser- vices and space, maritime and air transport), therefore, reducing foreign competition in specific fast-growing sectors, as well as in others with a strong public involvement. The limitations in forms of establishment applied both horizontally and vertically imply a preference for greenfield investment over acquisition of existing Chinese companies. This also demonstrates a marked preference for JVs, allowing control, but with Chinese interests involved. In its MFN exemptions, China lists maritime transport (international transport, freight and passengers); the parties concerned may, through bilateral agreements, establish entities to engage in business in China, \u201csubject to Chinese laws on joint ventures and on foreign-capital enterprises for ships owned or operated by carriers of the parties to the agreement\u201d. In addition, China has listed cargo-sharing agreements with Algeria, Argentina, Bangladesh, Brazil, Thailand, US and Zaire. 6.3.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI In China, services are characterized by state involvement through state owned enterprises and restrictions on involvement of the private sector. There is gradual liberalization in the Chinese services sector with certain ser- vices activities, particularly wholesale and retail, catering, real estate, storage and transport, having a sizeable private sector presence. However, equity restrictions or prohibitions still operate for most of the services. China\u2019s TPR of 2006, has noted that, \u201cin liberalizing services, China has tended to follow closely its commitments under the GATS rather than liberalize autonomously, although its GATS commitments tend, in general, to be more extensive than those of other developing countries.\u201d Telecommunication services Before China\u2019s accession to the WTO, the Chinese telecommunication market was closed to foreign inves- tors. At present, foreign investment in the sector is regulated by the \u201cProvisions on Administration of Foreign Invested Telecommunications Enterprises\u201d (promulgated by Decree No. 333 of the State Council on 11 Decem- ber 2001 and effective as of 1 January 2002). These provisions brought foreign equity limits in conformity with China\u2019s GATS commitments. Foreign equity up to 49 percent for basic telecom services and up to 50 percent for value-added telecom services was allowed. Further, the largest Chinese and foreign investor in a foreign invested enterprise (FIE) was allowed to hold up to 30 percent equity of the enterprise. For an FIE to obtain a telecom services license, the Chinese partner must submit a proposal to the appropriate authority, along with the project proposal, a feasibility study report and the relevant documents certifying the compliance of the foreign and Chinese investors with the provisions and other conditions in the Regulations on Telecom- munications. Under China\u2019s GATS commitments, there are foreign equity restrictions (25 percent for fixed line and 49 percent for mobile services), and for some services, geographic restrictions. However, in practice, foreign in- vestment in fixed line and mobile services falls below these limits. In value-added services foreign investments are encouraging with around 80 percent of enterprises having domestic non-public or foreign ownership. 28 Financial services Restrictions on the operations of foreign banks have declined gradually. Foreign banks came to China in the early 1980s, but were allowed to do so only through representative offices. Since then, reforms have gradually opened up the sector and foreign banks are permitted to establish branches in China. However, this is still subject to restrictions which can be geographic, product or client specific in character. After its accession to the WTO, China has committed to permit foreign investment in the banking sector without geographic or client restrictions by the end of 2006. The \u201cRegulations on Administration of Foreign Financial Institutions and its Implementing Rules\u201d deter- mine the rules under which foreign and foreign-funded banks may operate in China, while the \u201cAdministrative Rules Governing the Equity Investment in Chinese Financial Institutions by Overseas Financial Institutions\u201d regulate equity investment by foreign financial institutions. These rules place a series of restrictions in the way in which foreign financial institutions operate in China. Foreign equity in the financial services sector is restricted and follows China\u2019s GATS commitments, which commit to a gradual opening up of the sector to foreign competition.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b99d9668-83a5-493a-9dac-00f82d805d61": {"__data__": {"id_": "b99d9668-83a5-493a-9dac-00f82d805d61", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "acda751fc4ef63227cef479b293f6f4996c5939c5123b899ae607d5adea120b8"}, "2": {"node_id": "b3e7e3cf-f1c8-40f0-bd5c-4c9457f042c9", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ef56cc7844ed9bb11af86500dc921f2c95705cd8ae62e5ba3b6166365de900c5"}}, "hash": "624539026b148c1bcf3dc7bd638a7ba863794c3194cc0b7841f72b5f89154951", "text": "Equity held by a single overseas financial institution in a Chinese financial institution is not allowed to exceed 20 percent. At the end of June 2005, there were 225 licensed foreign banks operating in China representing 68 banks from 19 nations. Out of these, 173 were foreign bank branches while", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "743b3df7-8ffe-4084-b660-8571f193a329": {"__data__": {"id_": "743b3df7-8ffe-4084-b660-8571f193a329", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fda7461079640dd991e223bc583e4dc4e287a4eaf0fb3b99f9cd2a37f1ca7310"}}, "hash": "fda7461079640dd991e223bc583e4dc4e287a4eaf0fb3b99f9cd2a37f1ca7310", "text": "six banks were local subsidiaries of foreign banks. Among them, 133 were permitted to conduct business in the local currency, 15 were allowed to operate on-line banking, 41 were allowed to deal in derivatives and five were permitted to conduct trust business under the Qualified Foreign Institutional Investor (QFII) scheme. By the end of 2004, 18 Chinese cities were open to foreign banks to provide local currency services, and two of these cities opened up to foreign banking one year ahead of schedule. Local currency business was opened to foreign banks in two other cities in December 2005. In an attempt to encourage investment in the less prosperous parts of the country, the review and approval procedures for foreign bank branch applications in China\u2019s Western and North-Eastern areas were relaxed for conducting local currency business. Under these relaxed requirements, instead of assessing the profitability of each individual branch when considering the application, the regulatory authority would con- sider the profitability of all Chinese branches of the foreign bank. A \u201cgreen passage\u201d has thus been established for foreign banks wishing to provide services in Western and North-Eastern regions. China\u2019s TPR of 2006, notes that the government has concentrated efforts on improving governance and raising supervisory standards to international levels as well as increasing transparency and competition in the sector, with increase in foreign presence being one way of achieving these goals. The Bank of America currently holds nine percent shares of China Construction Bank (CCB), while Asia Financial Holdings Private Limited, a company belonging to the Singapore government\u2019s holding company, Temasek, holds 5.1 percent of CCB shares. This is indicative of China\u2019s willingness to allow foreign investments in its financial services sector. In the insurance sector, out of a total of 80 providers, there are 37 foreign providers, most of which are branches, and few are joint ventures. The foreign insurance providers were subject to geographic restrictions until the end of 2004, and they are not allowed to write compulsory insurance, like motor third party liability. In 2004, foreign non-life insurance companies accounted for little more than one percent of non-life insurance 29 premiums in China, while foreign life insurance companies had little more than two percent share of the life insurance market. Foreign insurance companies are permitted to enter the market as 100 percent foreign-owned subsid- iaries for non-life insurance and up to 50 percent foreign-owned for life insurance. With regard to MA through commercial presence, foreign non-life insurers were initially to be permit- ted to establish branches and joint ventures with maximum of 51 percent foreign ownership. However, within two years from China\u2019s accession to the WTO (December 2003), foreign non-life insurance providers were to be permitted to establish themselves as wholly owned subsidiaries, and the TPR for China indicates that this took place on schedule. Foreign life insurers are permitted to establish through joint ventures, but their ownership is restricted to 50 percent of total equity. In addition, the \u201cRules on Administration of Insurance Companies\u201d restricts a single foreign shareholding to 20 percent and all foreign shareholding in such joint ventures to 25 percent. Transport services In January 2005, there were 28 independent civil airlines in China, all considered to be national carriers. Of the 28 carriers, 18 were state-owned or partially state-owned, and eight have foreign equity participation. Regulations stipulate that foreign equity in a domestic airline must not exceed 49 percent. According to the \u201cProvisions on Foreign Investment in Civil Aviation\u201d, foreign investors may not exclusively own and operate airports and airport services and a Chinese national must have majority control. For foreign investments in maritime transportation, general regulations are contained in Maritime Transportation Regulations, and detailed regulations are provided in the \u201cAdministrative Rules on Foreign Investment in the International Maritime Transportation Industry\u201d, which became effective on June 1, 2004. Joint ventures with FDI are allowed to engage in international shipping services, international shipping agency services, international ship management services, loading and unloading of international shipments and international maritime container freight station and container yard services; joint ventures and wholly foreign-owned enterprises may offer routing services for their own or operated vessels and international maritime cargo warehousing services. Requirements, application documents and procedures are in general similar to those for domestic enterprises. Additional requirements for FIEs include the stipulation that the proportion of foreign investment in international shipping operators should not exceed 49 percent. Under the \u201cCatalogue for the Guidance of Foreign Investment Industries\u201d, FDI is encouraged in inter- national liner and tramp maritime transport, and in international container multi-modal transport business. For the former, foreign investment may not exceed 49 percent of total", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c2a4dd7e-b62c-487d-ab44-d2bb99f437b9": {"__data__": {"id_": "c2a4dd7e-b62c-487d-ab44-d2bb99f437b9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e5a2ea18a0a08918718e67625b1b5c7d12edf899708a932bbc319babe9415a3d"}, "3": {"node_id": "4dbb59e2-1e22-4504-a75b-fd9c42eb3b8f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b0debd8eb345c428b197dd0fcbbffe1c9af1665c942e3d037883129b157504bc"}}, "hash": "785834ac11182a89eb3613a83c048e80c271db406927f7df7e43274c9e9143a0", "text": "equity; while for the latter, 100 percent foreign equity ownership was permitted from December 11, 2005. Foreign investment in shipping agencies, freight forwarding agencies and cargo handling for foreign vessels are in the restricted category. For shipping agencies, the proportion of foreign investment cannot exceed 49 percent of total equity. For freight forward- ing agencies, 100 percent foreign ownership has been permitted since December 11, 2005, and for cargo handling for foreign vessels, foreign investment can only take the form of joint ventures. Foreign investment in port construction and management is listed as \u201cencouraged\u201d in China\u2019s \u201cCata- logue for the Guidance of Foreign Investment Industries\u201d. Foreign investors can establish wholly owned port operators or set up joint ventures. In 2005, there were over 200 FIEs involved in port services in China. 6.3.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed to 41.1 percent of China\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007). Major service activities include wholesale and retail trade and catering services, finance, insurance and social services. 30 Historically, the services market in China has been heavily regulated with significant restrictions on access to foreign services\u2019 providers. In general terms, the Chinese WTO commitments represent the \u2018most radical services program ever in the WTO history as well as in liberalization history\u2019 (Xuan 2003). It has been argued that the wide range of commitments agreed to by China under GATS cannot simply be equated with an unfounded and risky enterprise leading to a rather dramatic loss of policy space. Rather there existed an endogenous Chinese reform logic of providing political cover for the Chinese government to resist well organized protectionist, but inefficient Chinese state owned enterprises which were opposed to attempts at economic reform (Xuan 2003). It is beyond the scope of this paper to analyze the balance of considerations of whether or not China agreed to take on these commitments on account of endogenous logic or accession related pressures. China has submitted revised offers as part of the ongoing GATS (2000) negotiations, but the same is not yet de-restricted and has hence not been referred to in this analysis. As discussed in the section on autonomous liberalization and as seen from the TPR for China, the pace and quality of autonomous liberalization on Mode 3 issues in the realm of services has been defined by the commitments made by China during its accession to the WTO. This phenomenon needs to be analyzed in the context of the growing aspiration of China to make services the fulcrum of GDP growth. The growing ecological hazards in China resulting from two plus de- cades of manufacturing led growth are now making China focus on the services led growth model. Chinese authorities seem to have utilized GATS as a platform to implement the first round of services sector reforms at the domestic level without sacrificing their capacity to regulate the unfolding liberalization. This is sup- ported by China\u2019s commitments in the educational services sector. As noted in China Daily, \u201cAlthough China has promised foreign education institutions access to its educational service market via a \u201ccommercial pres- ence\u201d and \u201cmajority ownership,\u201d this does not necessarily mean foreign educational institutions can violate China\u2019s existing non-profit principle for the educational industry. China only promises \u201cMA\u201d and a guarantee of \u201cmanagement rights.\u201d Foreign educational institutions launching non-profit schools and other educational institutions in China may enjoy tax concessions or make moderate profits by organizing lawful activities; the profits, however, must be used to further their educational services in China and cannot be used as economic returns or distributed as bonuses to the administrative and teaching staff\u201d.52 6.4 India 6.4.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments India has scheduled commitments in six services sectors (business, communication, construction, financial services, health services and tourism). \uf06c Business services; construction and related engineering services; health and related social services; tour- ism; and travel related services: Foreign investments are allowed through incorporation with a foreign equity ceiling of 51 percent. \uf06c Communication services: Commitment in telecommunication services, subject to licensing require- ments and with a foreign-equity ceiling of 25 percent. Also, committed to open up the distribution of audiovisual products, but only through a representative office and with quantitative limitations on the number of products. 52 China Daily (2006). 31 \uf06c Financial services: Representations of foreign insurance companies are allowed but with strict limitations on their scope of business.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4dbb59e2-1e22-4504-a75b-fd9c42eb3b8f": {"__data__": {"id_": "4dbb59e2-1e22-4504-a75b-fd9c42eb3b8f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metada