: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "327e2204b2c681a013082cb0006fa3acb5f0f63a0284da05e87f5b63de3206fb"}, "3": {"node_id": "3c7d75cc-74a0-4782-b2eb-f54167462819", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "236399d724f659c62462b55db449aa4759cfe9c9ab573aada888a7ee05533853"}}, "hash": "322870dae1694db3a34d05910a44a6951c5ea0bedc7492969dcd1451e91938bb", "text": "the market share of foreign companies in the banking sector to 15 percent. For other financial services, MA was allowed under JVs with a 51 percent foreign-equity ceiling. \uf06c MFN exemptions have been scheduled for: Communication services (audiovisual and telecommunica- tion); recreational; and transport services. India shows a typical case of selective liberalization. Except for the infrastructural sectors, entry is allowed in business services, construction, health and tourism, promoting greenfield investment and allow- ing foreign control, though with Indian interests involved, perhaps with a technology-transfer objective. In finance and telecommunications, India\u2019s schedule provides a great deal of room for selected policies, allowing some foreign competition, but without jeopardizing the future development of the local industry. 6.4.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Business services Engineering services are a significant input in various activities that are open to foreign investment, but restrictions placed by India\u2019s GATS commitments for MA in this sub-sector continue. Commercial presence is allowed through incorporation, with a foreign equity ceiling of 51 percent. India did not make any GATS commitments with respect to legal services and foreign investment is still not allowed in this sector. Financial services Financial services, particularly banking and insurance continue to have a significant presence in state-owned companies, but competition is being encouraged in this sector. Restrictions on foreign banks have been relaxed. In 2006-07, of the 89 scheduled commercial banks, 29 were foreign banks.53 All commercial banks, including foreign banks, are still required to allocate a certain percentage of net lending (40 percent for domestic banks and 32 percent for foreign banks) to priority sectors (including agriculture and small-scale industries).54 Structural reforms have continued to increase the competitiveness of the banking sector and reduce risks. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI), India\u2019s central Bank, has been introducing prudential requirements to align the banking sector with international practices. Banks were required to implement the Basel II capital adequacy framework by March 2007. However, this requirement has been postponed to March 31, 2008 for foreign banks operating in India. In February 2005, the RBI formulated the \u201cRoadmap for Presence of Foreign Banks in India\u201d and the \u201cGuidelines on Ownership and Governance in Private Banks\u201d. Measures have also been adopted to gradu- ally lift restrictions on foreign banks, while certain limits on foreign competition will remain until 2009. For example, although in 2003-04 the aggregate foreign investment limit was increased from 49 percent to 74 percent in domestic private banks identified by the RBI for restructuring, the RBI has not laid down any criteria for identifying weak private-sector banks in need of restructuring, nor has it identified any bank for restructur- ing. In addition, the 49 percent limit remains for other private-sector banks until 2009. 53 Visit http://rbidocs.rbi.org.in/rdocs/Publications/PDFs/80008.pdf, accessed 24 November 2007. 54 Visit http://rbi.org.in/scripts/BS_ViewMasterCirculars.aspx?Id=3648&Mode=0, accessed 24 November 2007. 32 Furthermore, under India\u2019s GATS commitments, foreign banks were allowed to access the Indian mar- ket only through branches (i.e. wholly owned subsidiaries or joint ventures were not allowed). Restrictions were also imposed on the number of banking licences (12 per year for new entrants as well as existing banks), and on the value of the banking system\u2019s assets in the hands of foreign banks (15 percent of total assets). The Roadmap issued by the RBI in February 2005, divided foreign participation in the banking sector into two phases. In the first phase, foreign banks were allowed to establish wholly owned subsidiaries, in addition to branches. At present all 29 foreign banks in India are branches. So far, no foreign bank has set up a wholly owned subsidiary in India. In the second phase, to commence in April 2009, foreign banks may be permitted to enter into M&As with any private bank in India, subject to the overall investment limit of 74 percent. The insurance industry in India is still dominated by state owned enterprises. Competition in the indus- try is constrained by the relatively high entry barriers. Foreign investment is restricted to 26 percent of total investment, though it is believed that the government is considering raising this limit to 49 percent.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3c7d75cc-74a0-4782-b2eb-f54167462819": {"__data__": {"id_": "3c7d75cc-74a0-4782-b2eb-f54167462819", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Na