69b82085e56": {"__data__": {"id_": "099d556b-350a-4aee-8379-a69b82085e56", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "289af5bd5ec8e7c3e5d8b675fc80c32100ef25c1a0e6946692e747ace6912453"}}, "hash": "289af5bd5ec8e7c3e5d8b675fc80c32100ef25c1a0e6946692e747ace6912453", "text": "percent to 74 percent in certain areas, such as fixed line, cellular, unified access services and national and international long-distance calls services. Construction and related engineering services The policy focusing on improving road connectivity across India has brought about significant investment in road development. Up to 100 percent FDI has been permitted in the road sector since 1997. International competitive bidding is used for projects financed by international lending agencies and for larger projects for which sufficient numbers of domestic consultants or contractors are not available. Presently, there are 46 foreign contractors from 27 countries working on 85 different projects sanctioned by the National Highway Authority of India (NHAI). NT is provided to foreign investors, though for registration purposes, proof of resi- dence is needed. Transport services India had not made commitments at GATS under transport services, but has been slowly liberalizing this sector as well. Rail transport is reserved for the state and is a state-owned monopoly. However, private participation and foreign investment is permitted in many non-core areas and activities, including hospitality (tourism and catering) and construction and management of freight terminals and operations. Public private partnerships (PPPs) are being encouraged in infrastructure construction projects. Reform measures have also been adopted to increase the competitiveness of maritime transportation services.100 percent foreign investment is allowed in the shipping sector, including coastal shipping. In the ports sectors as well, foreign investment restrictions have been relaxed. There is no approval requirement for up to 51percent foreign investment in projects providing supporting services to water trans- port. Automatic approval is granted for proposals with up to 100 percent foreign equity in construction and maintenance of ports and harbours; and the private sector is invited to participate in open tenders on a BOT basis. 33 In the air transport sector, although foreign investment by individuals has now been substantially liberalized with up to 49 percent foreign equity participation being permitted in the domestic sector and up to 100 percent in the case of non resident Indians, foreign airlines are not allowed to invest in the domestic sector. This constitutes a barrier both to foreign investment and the technology transfer that it can bring. Health services India allows 100 percent ownership for FDI, subject to approval by the Foreign Investment Promotion Board for investment in the Indian healthcare market by international investors. Indian private-sector operators have been setting up hospitals as joint ventures in collaboration with foreign investors (e.g. from Singapore and Malaysia). So far, India has not undertaken any GATS commitments in medical and dental services. 6.4.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed 54.7 percent to India\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007). The growth and employment trajectory of India is being defined by services for more than half a decade. Services have put India on the global map of international investment flows and trade. It is therefore not surprising to see India taking mea- sures to infuse confidence within the international community about its readiness to engage on international platforms to create more predictability and stability about its services liberalization programme. India is therefore one of the few developing Asian countries which has made revised offers as a part of the ongoing GATS (2000) negotiations. In the Doha Round, India has submitted both initial and revised offers. In its revised offer, India has included commitments in a number of new sectors or sub-sectors, and improvements to existing commitments in a number of sectors. However, India has received several plurilat- eral requests from groups wherein India is expected to improve upon its Mode 3 commitments on a sector by sector basis and ensure that horizontal limitations in MA and NT do not undermine the Mode 3 commitments. (Das 2006). New commitments in the revised offer include, inter alia, air transport services; architectural, integrated engineering, and urban planning and landscape services; construction and related engineering services; dis- tribution services; educational services; environmental services; life insurance services and services auxiliary to insurance; recreational, cultural and sporting services; tourism services; and veterinary services. Improve- ments to existing commitments include asset management and other non-banking financial services, banking services, computer and related services, construction and related engineering services, engineering services, research and development services and basic telecommunications and value-added telecommunications services. It is evident that India has moved beyond its GATS commitments in some sectors by increasing the amount of foreign investment allowed, for example in banking and health services. However, in some other sectors like engineering services it has not made any changes. With respect to legal services, foreign invest- ment is still not allowed. While commitments made by India at the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8562cbf7-b03d-4a92-928a-5f9122220fba": {"__data__": {"id_": "8562cbf7-b03d-4a92-928a-5f9122220fba", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5ce067d495a13bd6b1d352092cdf5b408a72c944b2bbc3c77a79fb6e0140e962"}, "3": {"node_id": "8dee9369-fe44-474b-953c-ac5804402f9f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "08728a83618694797e00085aceac6f96663f7c612d7fcd8c65da72a90d85491c"}}, "hash": "43b0553b59f938978abc5585ed01444652fc2e9d1381906e255d57f7aa078005", "text": "end of Uruguay Round of Trade Negotiations under GATS were far restrictive in comparison to its autonomous liberalization, its revised offers are in line with what India is offering at an autonomous level. While India is scheduling commitments under the GATS (2000) negotia- tions, it is also taking efforts to create regulatory institutions that can effectively regulate the outcomes of such scheduling in the future. 34 A common condition for foreign investment in most of the sectors scheduled by India is incorporation of the company in India and a limit on foreign equity investment. The requirement of local incorporation ensures that in the case of violation of legal provisions, the representatives of the locally incorporated office can be made accountable. Limits on foreign investment ensure greater partnerships between Indian and foreign investors, and facilitate transfer of business know-how. \u2018Commitments on enhanced levels of foreign equity participation\u2019 under Mode 3, have raised concerns including about commercialization of social services such as higher education and health facilities. Also, the ability of developing countries to regulate foreign service providers may be impacted since under GATS a similar regulatory treatment would have to be extended to foreign service providers as applied to domestic ones.55 6.5 Indonesia 6.5.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments Indonesia has submitted GATS commitments under six service sectors (business, telecommunications, con- struction, finance, maritime transport and tourism). As a horizontal restriction, Indonesia has committed to grant MA to foreign investors only through representative offices and JVs with a foreign-equity ceiling of 49 percent. It has also scheduled NT restrictions in land ownership, professional qualification requirements and taxation. The criteria, scope and procedures of the qualification requirements have not been included. \uf06c On all its service sectors, Indonesia has placed more restrictive foreign-equity ceilings than the 49 per- cent of the horizontal commitments (when local incorporation is allowed), except for tourism, where full ownership is granted, based on geographic limitations. \uf06c Communication services: Indonesia also limited foreign equity participation in all sub-sectors to 35 percent. The number of telecommunications suppliers is limited (Indonesia reserved many sub-sectors in telecommunications for PT Telkom, PT Indosat and PT Satelindo) sometimes under public monopoly, by a licensing system. \uf06c Transport services: MA has been granted only for representative offices in maritime transport, and under temporary unions of companies or joint operation in business services. \uf06c Financial services: Full foreign ownership is allowed in the non-banking financial sector, if the existing company is listed on the stock exchange, while granting access to other forms of establishment. In bank- ing, foreign banks are allowed to establish one branch in the country. \uf06c In MFN exemptions, Indonesia has provided for preferential short-listing for construction companies from the Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries for government-funded projects. In banking, licences are to be granted only to JV banks under reciprocity basis. Standards and qualification requirements, applied not only to the foreign investor, but to the Indone- sian party, ensures the capacity needed for effective technology transfer, and where the capacity is lacking, as in the non-banking financial sector, employment and training requirements would tend to enhance it. Conditions imposed in the tourism sector also seem to complement and enhance the local supply of services in disadvantaged regions. 55 Visit http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2227/stories/20060113002104400.htm, accessed 28 November 2007. 35 6.5.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Financial services With respect to the GATS, Indonesia bound its multilateral obligations at less than status quo in the financial sector. It is believed that this reflects the Indonesian government\u2019s dual objectives of trying to encourage foreign investment in the financial sector while providing national suppliers the time to develop necessary market infrastructure and institutional capabilities in order to create a well-functioning national market in line with the principle of progressive liberalization. Foreign interest in the sector has been strong, and by the end of 2005, foreign investors owned an estimated 40 percent of Indonesia\u2019s banking sector assets. Starting in early 2002, foreign banks began to purchase controlling interests in large domestic banks that had fallen into the hands of the government after the financial crisis. The \u201cdivestation programme\u201d in Indonesia resulted in a significant increase in foreign ownership in the national banking system. Foreign investors are allowed to own up to 99 percent of the paid- up capital in national commercial banks.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8dee9369-fe44-474b-953c-ac5804402f9f": {"__data__": {"id_": "8dee9369-fe44-474b-953c-ac5804402f9f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5ce067d495a13bd6b1d352092cdf5b408a72c944b2bbc3c77a79fb6e0140e962"}, "2": {"node_id": "8562cbf7-b03d-4a92-928a-5f9122220fba", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "43b0553b59f938978abc5585ed01444652fc2e9d1381906e255d57f7aa078005"}}, "hash": "08728a83618694797e00085aceac6f96663f7c612d7fcd8c65da72a90d85491c", "text": "Towards the end of 2005, 37 foreign banks boasted of a combined market share of 40 percent of the total banking industry. In the insurance sector, foreign companies are allowed to hold up to 80 percent stake in local insurance companies. This also goes beyond Indonesia\u2019s GATS commitments in the insurance", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "81948696-b69f-445f-a665-58c2cc421c68": {"__data__": {"id_": "81948696-b69f-445f-a665-58c2cc421c68", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d8f28bba994f79907256cb257d3d563fb9f3a8a8035301eec7210a8e05ea9c79"}, "3": {"node_id": "3129ddf5-de80-47fd-89eb-cd9158bc33f6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aba7631b589f9bf8d77667e7c83e54b707cc93448b6da46d665c8b9e8d6e498b"}}, "hash": "a45b1341151f0663de4de663d10a75f0818445193a723e73cffdd001a75780cd", "text": "sector. Telecommunication services Foreign investments are welcomed in the Indonesian value-added telecom market. Indonesia has been un- dertaking significant reform of its telecom policy. Over the past decade, a set of first generation reforms has resulted in increasing private sector and foreign participation. The provisions of Indonesia\u2019s Telecommunications Law have guided reforms to end monopolies and open basic telecommunications services to majority foreign ownership. It lifted Telkom\u2019s and Indosat\u2019s respec- tive monopolies on domestic and international services in 2002 as a first step towards introduction of full competition by the end of 2006, a target which has been moved forward from 2010. The law lays out goals that exceed many of the commitments Indonesia agreed to under the WTO Basic Telecommunications Agreement (for example, maximum foreign investment limit of 35 percent for tele- communications services companies).The law also removed previous requirements that prospective foreign investors have to partner or enter into a revenue-sharing arrangement with a state-owned enterprise. Transport services Government Regulation No. 20 (1994) allowed up to 95 percent foreign investment in shipping ventures. This is far above the 49 percent limit on foreign equity prescribed in Indonesia\u2019s horizontal commitments under GATS. Other services Foreign law firms seeking to enter the market are required to establish a joint venture with a local firm and in order to practice, all lawyers have to hold Indonesian citizenship and a degree from an Indonesian legal facility. Foreign investments in the retail and wholesale sectors are permitted, but on the condition that the investor enters into a partnership agreement with a small-scale Indonesian enterprise. There is also a ban on all foreign investment in the broadcast and media industry. 36 Foreign construction firms can form joint ventures with local partners in areas where the government considers that a local firm is unable to do the work. 6.5.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed 46.3 percent to Indonesia\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007). Wholesale and retail trade dominates the Indonesian services sector, followed by transport, storage and communication, real estate and business services and financial services. Indonesia submitted its conditional initial offer in the WTO services negotiations in April 2005. The offer does not significantly change Indonesia\u2019s existing GATS commitments, which cover about one third of all services sub-sectors and come with significant limitations on MA, such as joint venture requirements and for- eign equity caps. In the offer, Indonesia has proposed commitments in a number of professional and business services; telecommunications; construction and engineering services; educational services; financial services; health services; tourism; and maritime cargo handling. Together with other ASEAN members, Indonesia is seeking progress in the negotiation of Emergency Safeguard Measures (ESM) under Article X of the GATS. Indonesia did not submit a revised offer. It has also refrained from scheduling its largest services sector, viz. wholesale and retail trade sector even in its conditional initial offers made under GATS (2000) negotia- tions. Indonesia\u2019s earlier experience of banking sector liberalization during the 1990\u2019s, considered as the trig- ger of the protracted financial crisis in 1997, underlines the need for putting in place appropriate safety nets and other regulatory and institutional frameworks while making its offers (Warouw 2006, 97-111). In line with its cautious approach, Indonesia has made initial offers conditionally on the outcome of negotiations on ESM (Warouw 2006). Indonesia has taken the lead in suggesting a possible framework to govern the application of ESM for trade in services.56 6.6 Republic of Korea 6.6.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments The Republic of Korea has committed to eight services under GATS (business, communication, construction and related engineering services, distribution, environmental, financial, tourism and transport). \uf06c Business services: In accounting and taxation services, sole proprietorships or incorporated partnerships licensed by the appropriate authority are permitted. \uf06c Communication services: For telecommunication services, a service supplier is required to be a licensed Korean juridical person. Also, it is stated that largest shareholder of Korea Telecom (KT) must be the government and aggregate foreign shareholding must not be more than 20 percent till December 31, 2000, and no more than 33 percent beyond that date. Republic of Korea is committed to allowing 100 percent foreign shareholding in many telecommunication sub-sectors.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3129ddf5-de80-47fd-89eb-cd9158bc33f6": {"__data__": {"id_": "3129ddf5-de80-47fd-89eb-cd9158bc33f6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d8f28bba994f79907256cb257d3d563fb9f3a8a8035301eec7210a8e05ea9c79"}, "2": {"node_id": "81948696-b69f-445f-a665-58c2cc421c68", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a45b1341151f0663de4de663d10a75f0818445193a723e73cffdd001a75780cd"}}, "hash": "aba7631b589f9bf8d77667e7c83e54b707cc93448b6da46d665c8b9e8d6e498b", "text": "\uf06c Construction services: The Republic of Korea is committed to permitting joint ventures with local com- panies and allowing the establishment of branches in a phased manner. 56 Visit http://www.ictsd.org/issarea/stsd/Resources/Docs/ASEAN_ESM.pdf,accessed 25 November 2007. 37 \uf06c Distribution services: The Republic of Korea subjected provision of certain distribution services (like wholesale trade centres, wholesale markets with floor space of more than 3000 square meters, etc.) by foreign investors to ENT. It placed some restrictions", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c6f0fca1-7d1e-4b2d-bf13-e91d3c31acac": {"__data__": {"id_": "c6f0fca1-7d1e-4b2d-bf13-e91d3c31acac", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "573983ab1fa19b600112c4f5a667fd87d51a31de180863105942281224c48094"}}, "hash": "573983ab1fa19b600112c4f5a667fd87d51a31de180863105942281224c48094", "text": "on operation of joint ventures or 100 percent foreign ownership, which were to be removed on January 1, 1996. \uf06c Environmental services: Only 25 service providers are allowed and establishment of commercial pres- ence is subject to the ENT. \uf06c Financial sector: The Republic of Korea undertook standstill commitments for limitation on MA where specific commitments were undertaken in the schedule of commitments. Commercial presence is al- lowed only to foreign banks\u2019, limitations on deposits, loans and foreign exchange services also prescribed. Commercial presence allowed to life and non-life insurance companies, but joint ventures with Korean life insurance companies are not allowed. Recruitment of insurance professionals is also restricted. \uf06c Tourism and travel related services: Only travel agencies supplying tourist guide services are allowed. \uf06c Transport services: Business areas for freight forwarding for rail transport were limited. In the provision of maritime transport for passenger and freight, there were no restrictions except that the Republic of Korea unbound itself from establishment of registered company for the purpose of operating a fleet under the national flag of the Republic of Korea. The Republic of Korea bound itself to open up the domestic market to foreign companies creating new businesses. However, this seems only completely true for business and tourism services, while a wide and tailored range of limitations exists for other sectors, shaping the way in which new competitors will affect the market, such as in construction and environmental services. In strategic sectors, such as transport, finance and telecom, other, more stringent, limitations were put in place. Though there is a marked preference for NT limitations to be scheduled horizontally in Asia, the Repub- lic of Korea makes more use of their potential in order to ensure that, on the one hand, there will be enough space to design development policies coherent with the Republic of Korea\u2019s international commitments and on the other, that the quality and involvement of the newcomer will positively affect industrial enhance- ment. 6.6.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Financial services The financial sector of the Republic of Korea has been considerably restructured. This is especially true for banking where policy reforms have focused since the Asian financial crisis. The entry, including location or type of services offered, of foreign bank branches in the Republic of Korea is unrestricted. The licensing requirements for foreign subsidiaries are the same as for domestic banks, and are in fact less stringent for foreign branches. With regard to foreign investment, full foreign equity is allowed in banks, subject to special permission. Foreign equity has risen, on average, from under 10 percent in 1998 to 30 percent in September 2003. A few banks in the Republic of Korea are majority foreign owned. There is no limit per se to the number of banking licenses, including foreign licenses, which can be issued if the prudential requirements for a licence are met. There is also no restriction on foreign ownership of non-bank institutions, including securities compa- nies and investment trust companies. Prudential regulations apply equally to domestic and foreign financial institutions, in accordance with internationally accepted standards. 38 In 2003, 39 foreign banks in the Republic of Korea operated 61 branches. Though entry of foreign bank subsidiaries in the Republic of Korea is unrestricted, none operated till 2003. However, market penetration of foreign banks has improved from representing 6.1 percent of assets in 2000 to 7.3 percent in 2003. The operation of foreign banks is still subject to certain other conditions like a separate licence must be obtained for each foreign branch, requirements relating to minimum operating funds and requirement of having expertise in the international banking business. Foreign insurers, including foreign branches, can obtain license to operate in the Republic of Korea. They are however, subject to the restriction of maintaining funds of at least Won 3 billion (I USD equals 1039 South Korean Won), if they want to do business with both Koreans and foreigners, or Won 500 million if mostly with foreigners, and Won 100 million if only with foreigners. At the end of 2003, of the 23 life insurance companies, three were foreign branches and five were foreign subsidiaries. There were 26 non-life insurers, of which 11 were foreign branches. Telecommunication services Telecommunications in the Republic of Korea has traditionally had a \u201crelatively high degree of government intervention and insufficient competition\u201d.57 The sector has been gradually deregulated and opened to com- petition, including from foreign providers, since the mid 1990\u2019s. All telecommunication markets are open to new entrants since 1998. The government no longer has any commercial interest in telecommunications after fully privatizing the dominant carrier, KT,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a2d3b74d-84d2-453c-98e2-b8c1003da464": {"__data__": {"id_": "a2d3b74d-84d2-453c-98e2-b8c1003da464", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7f154d5c7bbdfc8ba4e560972cc1e04ad68fc7d1e1ae9e8df2faeda5b242b542"}, "3": {"node_id": "7fefacc4-7d8f-4447-b1f7-3a41909e7159", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ab44f03017af7bee87d53487499ac881e8805a2022b40f56755c93e31b024d38"}}, "hash": "765bdf0164a3e37c91e32f9bd71a1244bd7abcc37c275c05e6ea99c9625640ab", "text": "in May 2002, when it sold its remaining 28 percent equity. The ceiling on foreign ownership of KT was also raised from 33 percent to 49 percent, as for other facility based service providers. The individual ownership limit of 15 percent was removed in August 2002. No foreign ownership limits apply to special telecom service providers or to value-added telecom service providers. The Republic of Korea has unilaterally liberalized its foreign ownership regime beyond its WTO obligations, and its telecom- munications sector has industrialized at a remarkable pace, reflecting the rapid spread of high-tech services and greater competition. Transport services In maritime transport, licensing of foreign shipping branches in the Republic of Korea has been relaxed, and foreign ownership of Korean vessels is allowed. Foreigners can also participate in coastal transportation of goods and passengers between North and South Korea as a minority (less than 50 percent) joint venture with a South Korean shipping company. 6.6.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed 57.2 percent to the Republic of Korea\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007). The Korean eco- nomic structure is transforming with the emergence of a strong services sector. Hi-tech services account for a lion\u2019s share in the Korean services sector given the value they unlock on being supplied. Given the decline of employment and growth in its manufacturing sector, the Korean government is focusing on boosting the competitiveness of its services sector \u201cto foster high-end services including finance, logistics, design and consulting. This will create quality jobs as well as making direct contribution to enhancing manufacturing competitiveness. In particular, upgrading and fostering education, culture, tourism and leisure services are called for from multi-faceted aspects\u201d.58 57 \u201cTrade Policy Review of Republic of Korea\u201d, WT/TPR/S/137, dated 15 and 17 September 2004, available at www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/ tpr_e/s137-4_e.doc 58 Ministry of Finance and Economy and Economic Information and Education Center, Korea Development Institute (2006). 39 The Republic of Korea submitted revised offers as a part of the ongoing GATS (2000) negotiations. This revised conditional offer covers improvement of MA or enhancement of transparency through clarifica- tion of the initial offer in horizontal commitments and services sectors in business services (legal services, veterinary services, services incidental to manufacturing), telecommunication services, distribution services, educational services, financial services and transport services. It improves upon the Republic of Korea\u2019s GATS commitments by placing fewer restrictions on foreign investors. The Republic of Korea has liberalized its financial and telecommunications sector significantly. Its revised offer indicates that it intends to ease restrictions on foreign investment in other service areas as well. The degree of liberalization in the Republic of Korea\u2019s services sector is comparable to that of the industrial- ized countries (Jong 2000). The Republic of Korea has been a proponent of \u201cbenchmarking\u201d in the services negotiation along with EC, Japan and Switzerland, which as discussed in the introduction, sought to set quantitative and qualitative targets for liberalization, in order to force the pace of negotiations which was not accepted by the developing countries on the grounds that it was contrary to the intent and purpose of the GATS agreement. The EU is the Republic of Korea\u2019s second largest trading partner and is currently engaged in talks for a bilateral free trade agreement. This may perhaps help to explain the liberal nature of commitments undertaken by the Republic of Korea in GATS. 6.7 Kyrgyz Republic 6.7.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments The Kyrgyz Republic has made significant GATS commitments in 11 service sectors, including telecommunica- tions and financial services, during WTO accession. However, it has not specified any horizontal commitments for service supply through Mode 3. \uf06c Business services: The Kyrgyz Republic has kept itself unbound in medical, veterinary services, services in the sphere of industrial property, real estate services and services incidental to fishing. In services incidental to energy distribution, there are no restrictions except for services on distribution of electric energy. In the legal services sector, there are no restrictions except only Kyrgyz citizens can practice as qualified Kyrgyz lawyers. \uf06c Communication services: The Kyrgyz Republic has kept itself unbound in the postal services sector, and is committed to removing all restrictions in telecommunications services from January 1, 2003.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7fefacc4-7d8f-4447-b1f7-3a41909e7159": {"__data__": {"id_": "7fefacc4-7d8f-4447-b1f7-3a41909e7159", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7f154d5c7bbdfc8ba4e560972cc1e04ad68fc7d1e1ae9e8df2faeda5b242b542"}, "2": {"node_id": "a2d3b74d-84d2-453c-98e2-b8c1003da464", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "765bdf0164a3e37c91e32f9bd71a1244bd7abcc37c275c05e6ea99c9625640ab"}}, "hash": "ab44f03017af7bee87d53487499ac881e8805a2022b40f56755c93e31b024d38", "text": "\uf06c Construction and related engineering services; distribution services, environmental services; health related and social services; tourism and travel related services; and recreational, cultural and sporting services (other than audiovisual services): N