was to be removed by January 1, 2002. No limitations were placed in the banking services sector. \uf06c Transport services: The Kyrgyz Republic kept itself unbound in the air transport services sector, and com- mitted to removing all restrictions in the maintenance and repair of aircrafts before 2005. \uf06c The Kyrgyz Republic made no MFN exemptions. 40 6.7.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Financial services The Kyrgyz Republic made comprehensive liberalizing GATS commitments during WTO accession. There are no non-prudential restrictions on foreign banks or other financial institutions, including insurance companies, which are privately owned. Foreign bank ownership is increasingly high at over 60 percent. 15 banks have foreign equity, of which 11 are majority overseas owned. In 1998, seven banks had foreign participation, and accounted for 21 percent of total bank assets. Foreign investment in banks has risen considerably over the years. The number of banking licences, including foreign licences is not fixed. While no ENTs are applied in approving applications, applicants must submit a business plan that includes an assessment of the bank\u2019s economic feasibility and provides the strategy, directions and scope of its activities for the first three years of operation. Foreign banks can offer the same services as Kyrgyz-owned banks, and the number of branches or their location is unrestricted. In the insurance sector, the 49 percent limit on foreign equity in insurance companies has been re- moved in line with Kyrgyz Republic\u2019s GATS commitments where it committed to remove this MA limitation by early 2002. Telecommunications The telecommunications market has been liberalized in line with the Kyrgyz Republic\u2019s WTO commitments. As per the Trade Policy Review, the Kyrgyz Republic has \u201cfull\u201d competition in all major telecommunication markets.59 The monopoly on international and long distance calls of the majority state owned national carrier, Kyrgyz telecom, was terminated from February 2003, in line with the country\u2019s GATS commitments. The Rus- sian company, Saima Telecom, and Winline provide competing fixed line services, such as local, long-distance and international calls and data transmission. There are several foreign-owned operators of cellular and pag- ing services, and the first foreign ISP was licensed in early 2003. There are no overseas ownership restrictions, and foreign and domestic operators enjoy the same rights, including access to the public network. While call back services are still prohibited, its anti-competitive impact has been diminished by the telecommunication sector\u2019s liberalization. Transport Transport services, other than road, are heavily regulated in the Kyrgyz Republic. Inter-city road transport is largely privatized. Five year licenses are given to operate inter-city and urban bus services and foreigners can apply for grant of such licences. No restrictions on foreign equity exist. Tourism According to Kyrgyz authorities, foreign investment in tourism has increased and is unrestricted. Foreigners can freely provide tourism services, and many of them do. A law was proposed restricting foreign ownership of tourist facilities to 49 percent, requiring the investment manager to be a Kyrgyz national and limiting the number foreigners in management to one-third, but it was not passed. 59 \u201cTrade Policy Review of Kyrgyz Republic\u201d, WT/TPR/S/170, dated 9 and 11 October 2006, available at www.wto.org/english/ tratop_e/tpr_e/s170-04_e.doc. 41 6.7.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS As a former centrally planned economy, the Kyrgyz Republic had practically no market for goods and services and the regulatory structure was underdeveloped. However, it did not receive the developing country status in the process of accession to the WTO despite the fact that it has a low GDP per capita with high poverty.60 In 2006, the services sector accounted for 46.9 percent of the GDP of Kyrgyz Republic (World Bank 2007). Among services, the largest sub-sectors in 2005 were wholesale and retail trade, transport and com- munications, education, construction and real estate. During 2005, while the gross domestic capital formation as a percentage of GDP was 14.4 percent, the gross domestic savings in Jordan as a percentage of GDP was - 4.7 percent.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "03bdb314-1c57-4e08-bdb0-19a910705d6a": {"__data__": {"id_": "03bdb314-1c57-4e08-bdb0-19a910705d6a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "06a787d9e745c234b13585b235182bda2e3eb505cb652ed76ad3af2e8f359929"}, "2": {"node_id": "ccf55b74-c5d1-48d4-9b78-2d78c0ebe7b1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9a7043c48be9c2fc5b129a91fa28cc0b0f12365a4745d5e967831079aae32688"}}, "hash": "f50365c4fbdf3bb50428927c01c2af82e6af3156570f421676ed3aab47850aac", "text": "This shows the dependency of the Kyrgyz Republic on international capital for financing the growth of its GDP and hence its services sector, a phenomenon similar to that faced by Jordan (World Bank 2006). It is in this context that one needs to analyze the commitments made by the Kyrgyz Republic at the autonomous level and at the WTO. The WTO Trade Policy of the Kyrgyz Republic carried out in 2007, clearly notes that the Kyrgyz Republic had made very liberal commitments and has been liberalizing its sectors in ac- cordance with those commitments.61 As a NAC, the Kyrgyz Republic had made a case for flexibility in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fb8527ec-72ad-4cbc-93f7-0626106581b9": {"__data__": {"id_": "fb8527ec-72ad-4cbc-93f7-0626106581b9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2b4f2d00ecbd8e9e5e3d4bc3e8b049920c3bc876e8fbfe8db3de766d50927296"}, "3": {"node_id": "5eb5d019-ee1a-4927-bd61-7a348f7d2421", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Pr