wholly owned by Nepalese nationals. \uf06c Business services: Foreign equity limits in different sub-sectors range from 51 to 80 percent. Incorpora- tion of the company in Nepal is also required. 60 Visit http://europeandcis.undp.org/uploads/public/File/YVERDON.WTOAccession_SPECA1.ppt, accessed 29 November 2007. 61 Visit www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/s170-02_e.doc, accessed 29 November 2007. 62 Visit http://www.ictsd.org/weekly/03-03-13/BRIDGESWeekly7-9.pdf, accessed 29 November 2007. 63 Visit www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/s170-02_e.doc, accessed 29 November 2007. 64 Visit http://europeandcis.undp.org/uploads/public/File/YVERDON.WTOAccession_SPECA1.ppt, accessed 29 November 2007. 42 \uf06c Communication services: There will not be any limit on the number of service providers from January 2009, for local, domestic and international telephone, telex and telegraph services. There will not be any limit on the number of service providers for mobile services after January 2009 as well. Foreign participa- tion is permitted through JVs with up to 80 percent of equity participation. \uf06c Construction and related engineering services; and health related and social services: No restriction, except that incorporation of the company in Nepal is required and a cap of 51 percent has been placed on foreign equity. \uf06c Distribution services: No restriction, except that incorporation in Nepal is required and a cap of 51 per- cent has been placed on foreign equity. This limit will be eased to 80 percent five years from accession. Nepal has kept itself unbound for wholesale and retailing services until it decides on the types of foreign entities who can provide this service. \uf06c Educational and environmental services: No restriction, except that incorporation in Nepal is required and a cap of 51 percent has been placed on foreign equity. This limit will be eased to 80 percent five years from accession. \uf06c Financial services: For reinsurance and retrocession, Nepal has kept itself unbound till December 31, 2007 and afterwards no restrictions will operate in this sub-sector. Nepal has kept itself unbound for certain financial services until it decides on the entities who can conduct these services, the legal framework is established and the business is authorized by the government. \uf06c Tourism and travel related services: No restrictions, except that incorporation in Nepal is required and foreign equity has been capped at 51 percent for travel agencies and tour operators, and at 80 percent for hotel, lodging services and graded restaurants.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5eb5d019-ee1a-4927-bd61-7a348f7d2421": {"__data__": {"id_": "5eb5d019-ee1a-4927-bd61-7a348f7d2421", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2b4f2d00ecbd8e9e5e3d4bc3e8b049920c3bc876e8fbfe8db3de766d50927296"}, "2": {"node_id": "fb8527ec-72ad-4cbc-93f7-0626106581b9", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c030a5b6aba721195cfa2b298f7a5e0faacd579e4de2eff6e08c842e673f6441"}}, "hash": "c6b3603c329f2a53dde307f9cb7dede422ae26d5893d1650182cc458618292de", "text": "\uf06c Recreational, cultural and sporting services: No restriction, except that incorporation in Nepal is required and foreign equity has been capped at 51 percent. Also, foreign investment should be a minimum of US$ one million. The limit on foreign equity will be eased to 80 percent after five years from accession. \uf06c Transport services: No restriction, except that incorporation in Nepal is required and foreign equity has been capped at 51 percent. For maintenance and repair of aircrafts and for computer reservation systems, the cap will be increased to 80 percent after five years from accession. Nepal has allowed, through its schedule, entry of foreign companies only through the establishment of new businesses (favouring greenfield investment) in practically all services sectors, only conditional to the participation of Nepalese nationals. 6.8.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Recent government policy changes have signalled to foreign", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5a247c98-2083-4539-bffb-3070be57c89e": {"__data__": {"id_": "5a247c98-2083-4539-bffb-3070be57c89e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "67a88717b8e31d0d10be8d35c694dcd1dec6135c751d2630dfefebabc7cc2fee"}, "3": {"node_id": "1fddde4b-26c5-4e9e-bb71-3e8b01f4570f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2f4bf1eb0918f72c344ba916f4f73abf79c8402e2dc39866ac588b86ea40443f"}}, "hash": "7132a790d64a3d22fad9e7029c81c781fdd0e31a9d73255a4fe50e5006bc1a50", "text": "investors that Nepal is open for business. In 2005, the government opened up certain service sectors to foreign investment. Progress has been made in allowing private operations in some sectors that were previously government monopolies, such as telecommunica- tions and civil aviation. Licensing and regulations have been simplified, and 100 percent foreign ownership has been allowed. In order to comply with its WTO commitments, Nepal recently opened service industries and a few other sectors to foreign investment. These sectors include business and management consulting, accounting, engineering and legal services, travel and trekking services, tourist lodging, international retail sales services and production of alcohol or cigarettes. However, foreign investment is forbidden in the defence sector. 43 In these recently opened service sectors, permitted foreign investment limits range from 51 to 80 percent while the balance of the investment is reserved for Nepali nationals in order to form a joint venture with a foreign investor. Though foreigners are generally free to establish and own business enterprises, the form of participa- tion is restricted in some cases. For example, foreign banks have not yet been allowed to open wholly-owned subsidiaries or branch operations in Nepal. 6.8.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed to around 40 percent of Nepal\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2006). With its accession to the WTO and liberalization commitments submitted under GATS, the country seems ready to increase this share significantly. Though Nepal\u2019s schedule of commitments reveals plans to liberalize 11 services sectors, this should not be misunderstood to be an automatic shrinkage of its policy space. Adhikari (2005) believes that Nepal has been able to maintain its policy space through selective liberalization and by specifying conditions on MA and NT: \u201cA few cautious approaches taken by Nepal include: a) capping foreign investment in most sectors at 51 percent; while in some others at 66-67 percent and only in two sectors at 80 percent; b) the requirement that a majority of the board members of basic telecom providers be Nepali nationals; and in the case of financial in- stitutions, composition of the board be proportionate to the shareholding pattern; c) allowing foreign banks, with minimum \u2018B\u2019 rating by a credit rating agency to establish branches in Nepal for wholesale banking (not retail banking); d) incentives and subsidies be available only to enterprises wholly owned by Nepali nationals; e) not allowing foreigners to purchase or own land in Nepal; and f) movement of natural person be limited to intra-corporate transferee at the executive, manager or specialist levels with a provision that the number of such transferees shall not exceed 15 percent of the number of local employees in the firm\u201d. Nepal did not submit revised offers as a part of the ongoing GATS (2000) negotiations, and the govern- ment has been moving towards competition in most sectors of the economy in accordance with its GATS commitments. As a NAC to the WTO, as in the case of others, Nepal has agreed to far reaching commitments in the services sector which would have significant post-accession implications, given the importance of services for macroeconomic performance and national development (Sauve 2005). It has been argued that the schedule of commitments of Nepal unmistakably shows an investor-friendly orientation with only narrow limitations included to guide FDI into priority sectors and activities that are expected to have strong develop- mental effects. However, the limitation on entry through new businesses and conditions for the participation of Nepalese nationals and domestic businesses has been introduced to ensure that Nepalese citizens benefit from new technologies introduced by foreign investors (Sauve 2005). 6.9 Pakistan 6.9.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments Pakistan has made commitments in six service sectors (business, communication, construction and related engineering, financial, health and tourism services). It has scheduled a horizontal limitation on MA by placing a foreign equity ceiling of 51 percent in all services sectors. Under horizontal limitation on national treatment, Pakistan has specified restrictions on ownership of land. \uf06c Business services: Pakistan places a cap of 40 percent foreign equity in engineering services in partner- ship with Pakistani engineers or engineering consultancy services. 44 \uf06c Communication services: Pakistan supplemented its commitments in the telecommunication services in the year 1997. Till 2003, many telecommunication sub-sectors were reserved for the state-owned Paki- stan Telecommunication Company Limited (PTCL) network. Pakistan kept itself unbound with respect to voice telephone services.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1fddde4b-26c5-4e9e-bb71-3e8b01f4570f": {"__data__": {"id_": "1fddde4b-26c5-4e9e-bb71-3e8b01f4570f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "