": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b298f252073fe22635f4082d9ed482b8fc64bb3162aadceaab72c8c268599ff6"}}, "hash": "b298f252073fe22635f4082d9ed482b8fc64bb3162aadceaab72c8c268599ff6", "text": "\uf06c Financial services: Pakistan\u2019s commitments in financial services, excluding insurance, are applicable to nationals and financial institutions of WTO member states whose laws and policies do not bar the provision of similar commitments to Pakistani nationals and financial institutions. Provision of banking services is also subject to injunctions regarding Islamic banking as laid down by competent courts in Pakistan. \uf06c Health related and social services: Provision of medical and dental services, and hospitals are subject to approval from the Pakistan Medical and Dental Council Regulations. \uf06c Tourism and travel related services: No restrictions on establishment of hotels, travel agencies etc. Contrary to many other countries in the region, Pakistan has not included further restrictions on NT at the horizontal level. It appears that too much attention has been given to foreign control, instead of other types of industrial policy measures that would discriminate among investors and types of investment, unless these concerns have been included in the licensing criteria, of which we are not aware. 6.9.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI The Pakistani government, at an autonomous level, has been consistently reducing state involvement in the services sector to encourage private investment in several activities. The Pakistan government\u2019s investment policy is geared towards encouraging foreign investment in all sectors of the economy. Foreign investment in Pakistan is fully protected through the Foreign Investment (Promotion and Protection) Act 1976, Protection of Economic Reforms Act 1992 and Foreign Currency Ac- counts (Protection) Ordinance, 2001. The Foreign Investment Act of 1976, provides that foreign investment will not be subject to higher income tax levels. A series of government agencies, most recently the Board of Investment in 1994, have been created to provide a one-stop interface between investors and Pakistani authorities. Mandatory foreign investor registration with the Board of Investment has been eliminated. However, foreign investors are still required to be registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission of Pakistan (SECP) and the State Bank of Pakistan (SBP), Pakistan\u2019s central bank. Previous requirement that foreign investors seek provincial government clear- ance for project location has also been removed. Reduction in FDI restrictions Restrictions on FDI in services have been progressively eased. Foreign investment at 100 percent equity on a repatriable basis is allowed in the services, infrastructure and social sectors. In June 2004, foreign investment in the services sector was further liberalized by removing the condition that a foreign investor has to accumulate 45 a minimum 40 percent Pakistani equity within five years of the initial investment. Now, the foreign investor can retain 100 percent equity for the lifetime of the investment. Minimum allowable equity investment in the non-financial services sector has been reduced from US$ 300,000 to US$ 150,000. Foreign investors are permitted to bid on the privatization of state-owned industries and financial institutions on terms equivalent to those offered to local investors. Communications services Full NT and legal protection has been provided to foreign investment in all but designated \u201csensitive\u201d sec- tors, which includes broadcasting. However, despite the exclusive rights of state entities in broadcasting and audiovisual, audiovisual services have been opened to joint ventures with foreign investors. There are no restrictions on FDI in telecommunication services and the liberalization process has been gaining ground since 2003. Private sector involvement in telecommunications has increased in activities other than the fixed line services. The government has identified telecom as a key sector for attracting overseas investment. Foreign investors in the telecom sector Egypt\u2019s Orascom which has investments in Mobilink, Nor- way\u2019s Telenor and the UAE-owned Warid Telecom were recently awarded GSM licences and two Luxembourg- based groups, Instafone and Paktel, are competing along with state-owned Ufone (Stewart 2004). The PTCL was privatized in 2006, paving the way for further competition in this sector. Financial services Through a change in the policies of the SBP, there are presently no restrictions on the number of branches a foreign bank can have. Like local banks, foreign banks are also required to submit an annual branch expansion plan to the SBP for approval. The SBP approves new branch openings based on the bank\u2019s net worth, adequacy of its capital structure, future earning prospects, credit discipline and the needs of the local population. Other services Investments in tourism, housing, construction and information technology sectors are being encouraged by granting \u201cindustry\u201d status to them. This implies that enterprises in these sectors are eligible for lower tax and utility rates than the commercial sector (which includes banks, insurance companies and other businesses). 6.9.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed around 52.9 percent to the GDP of Pakistan in 2006 (World Bank 2007) with a high", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5437a1ea-ace6-4836-8511-de6daf4c78fa": {"__data__": {"id_": "5437a1ea-ace6-4836-8511-de6daf4c78fa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba1cbc9b7835ad1569526a5893848128856e0ecb8c0f16bc740f8132103d1827"}}, "hash": "ba1cbc9b7835ad1569526a5893848128856e0ecb8c0f16bc740f8132103d1827", "text": "level of contribution coming from low end services. The services growth story in Pakistan is therefore volume driven rather than value driven. The unilateral liberalization process has involved relatively deeper commitments than at the GATS levels, and Pakistan has sought to preserve some policy space in its depth of commitments rather in coverage of sectors per se. In order to unlock value of its services, Pakistan requires foreign capital that can provide requisite technology and expertise. This could be one of the reasons for Pakistan adopting an ambitious autonomous liberalization regime in comparison to the commitments it has made under GATS. For example, Pakistan allows 100 percent foreign ownership at an autonomous level in all sectors in comparison to the horizontal ceiling of 51 percent foreign equity, introduced by it vis-\u00e0-vis its scheduled services under GATS. Given the far reaching liberalization commitments undertaken Pakistan has also been arguing for adequate ESM. 46 6.10 Philippines 6.10.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments The Philippines submitted commitments in four service sectors (communication, transport, financial and tourism sector). It significantly expanded commitments on financial services and on basic telecommunica- tions. However, it did not accept the Fourth (basic telecommunications) or Fifth (financial services) Protocols of the GATS. As a horizontal restriction on MA, the Philippines require all executive and managing officers to be citizens of the Philippines. The country also limits participation of foreign investors in the governing body of any corporate entity to proportionate share of foreign capital in such entities. Limitations on acquiring land have also been specified. NT limitations relating to peso borrowing by foreign firms are also specified. \uf06c Communication services: Only those corporations where at least 60 percent capital is owned by Filipinos are permitted to obtain authorization for operation of a public utility in all communications services. Provision of telecommunication services requires other certificates as well, like Franchise from Congress of the Philippines, and Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity from the National Telecommuni- cations Commission. \uf06c Financial services: In all sub-sectors of financial services, the appropriate regulatory authority in the Philippines decides whether public interest and economic conditions justify the establishment of com- mercial presence. In the banking sector, at least 70 percent of the banking assets in the country are required to be held by domestic banks with majority Filipino ownership. Limitations on the number of licenses and branches and their locations are also specified. Prior authorization is also required for a series of other banking activities. For many other financial services as well, foreign equity is limited to 40 percent. However, in life and general non-life insurance, foreign equity of 51 percent is allowed in voting stock of an existing local company or locally incorporated insurance company. Non-Filipino board members are restricted to one-third of the total strength of the board. \uf06c Tourism and travel related services: Foreign equity in tourism accommodation facilities is limited to 40 percent. However, there are no limits on foreign equity for a specialty restaurant which is not part of the facilities of a hotel. \uf06c Transport services: In transport services as well, those corporations where at least 60 percent capital is owned by Filipinos are permitted to obtain authorization for operation of a public utility in all transpor- tation services sectors. In passenger and freight transportation by road, the entry of new investors is subject to the ENT. The two factors considered for the purposes of the test are, first, the need to provide protection to investments of operators in un-served areas and second, the route measured capacity test for number of vehicles. 6.10.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Financial services The Philippines requires that 70 percent of bank assets must be held by domestic banks. Foreign banks are thus allowed to hold only 30 percent of bank assets. However, in 2004, foreign banks and their branches accounted for barely 14 percent of the bank assets in the Philippines. 47 The Philippines government has followed a policy of \u201cbank rationalization\u201d in recent years to reduce the number of small banks and consolidate the banking sector. In the year 2000, it issued a three year moratorium against the establishment of new banks in the country. This moratorium was intended to encourage bank buy outs, and was extended in duration. The ceiling of 60 percent of foreign ownership in domestic banks was lifted till June 2007, to allow foreign investors to own 100 percent of a bank. This was made subject to authorization of the Monetary Board in the Philippines. Establishment of new foreign bank branches remains \u2018effectively prohibited\u2019 because of the establish- ment of an additional ten", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "571bae28-dcec-4e0a-b28e-b882147d953d": {"__data__": {"id_": "571bae28-dcec-4e0a-b28e-b882147d953d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "feb6fccc343a25ef3b40259c4c4da7e934017ae7f6f4bb000afb100157c545c8"}}, "hash": "feb6fccc343a25ef3b40259c4c4da7e934017ae7f6f4bb000afb100157c545c8", "text": "foreign bank branches in the mid 1990s. However, foreign banks continue to have a significant presence as reflected in the ownership of private domestic commercial and universal banks. In 2003, less than half of these banks were 100 percent Filipino owned, and of the top 20 banks, only seven remained fully Filipino owned. Share of foreign equity is generally moderate, with only four of the top 20 banks with more than 20 percent. The TPR (2005) of the Philippines notes that the banking system in the Philippines in 1999 was more liberal than its GATS commitments. Though the moratorium could have reduced competition in the banking sector, it is difficult to measure its impact. In the insurance sector, 17 out of 141 insurance companies had majority foreign investment and five were domestically incorporated branches. Foreign insurance companies are allowed to operate as branches, subsidiaries or joint ventures if they had figured in the list of top 200 foreign companies in the world for the past 10 years. No limits on foreign equity have been placed. Foreign branches provide mainly non-life insur- ance, while foreign-owned companies offer both life and non-life policies. The insurance industry was opened up to 100 percent foreign ownership in 1994. However, minimum capital requirements increase with the degree of foreign ownership. Although there are no foreign ownership restrictions regarding the acquisition of shares of mutual funds, current law restricts membership on boards of directors to Philippine citizens. Tourism The Philippines government recognizes tourism as a top foreign exchange earner and allows 100 percent foreign equity in accommodation facilities, travel agencies, tour operators and organization of professional conferences. Full foreign equity is allowed in restaurants and domestic market enterprises if minimum paid up capital exceeds US$2.5 million and US$200,000 respectively, otherwise it is limited to 40 percent. Tourist transport services are constitutionally limited to Filipinos, and some other businesses dealing with tourists classified as retail services may be subject to a 40 percent investment ceiling. For tourist projects valued at a minimum of US$ 5 million, foreigners are allowed to lease land for 50 years instead of the usual period of 25 years, renewable for another 25 years. These measures indicate some progress beyond GATS in the tourism sector for the Philippines. 6.10.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS The services sector contributed to 53.2 percent of the Philippines\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007) and is the leading employer in the nation. The leading services sectors in the Philippines are tourism, communication, construction and finance. While the Philippines has been taking giant strides with respect to liberalizing their tourism and insurance sector at an autonomous level, they have preferred to remain conservative while open- ing these sectors under GATS. Moreover, the Philippines has not submitted any revised offers in the ongoing 48 GATS (2000) negotiations. Like the other ASEAN countries, the Philippines too has been demanding move- ment in the development of an ESM for services which has not progressed, in order to protect themselves from an import surge in services. 6.11 Sri Lanka 6.11.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments Sri Lanka scheduled commitments in only three services sectors (communication, financial and tourism services). Sri Lanka\u2019s specific commitments in the Uruguay Round covered only tourism. Subsequently, it participated in extended negotiations on basic telecommunications and financial services and accepted the GATS Fourth Protocol (basic telecommunications) and Fifth Protocol (financial services) on 27 November 1997 and 20 January 1999, respectively. While specifying horizontal commitments, Sri Lanka has notified a list of sectors where foreign invest- ments are not permitted (like pawn brokering, retail trade with a capital of less than US$ one million and businesses providing personal services other than for export of tourism). It also limited foreign equity up to 40 percent in a company proposing to carry out business activities relating to construction and residential buildings, mass transport, telecommunications, education, professional services, freight-forwarding, travel agencies and shipping agencies. \uf06c Communication: The monopoly on basic fixed wire telephony services (international) of the majority state-owned Sri Lanka Telecom was scheduled to last until at least 2000, when issuance of another licence would be conditional on satisfactory progress in tariff re-balancing. Sri Lanka also reserved the right to issue no new licences for mobile services until at least 2000 and to retain the duopoly on basic telephony services supplied by Wireless Local Loop (WLL) for five years (i.e. 2002). Foreign equity caps were scheduled, at 35 percent for Sri Lanka Telecom and 40 percent for other operators unless the Board of Investment (BOI) approved higher levels (up to 100 percent) on a case-by-case basis. Sri Lanka", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f7d3fee4-466c-446e-9016-8d8cf640848d": {"__data__": {"id_": "f7d3fee4-466c-446e-9016-8d8cf640848d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "75781a11108c5445ce37a55762e88dcd495c2a9077e42778b32fac0ade37d6ef"}}, "hash": "75781a11108c5445ce37a55762e88dcd495c2a9077e42778b32fac0ade37d6ef", "text": "adopted the Reference Paper on Regulatory Principles as an additional GATS commitment. \uf06c Financial services: Sri Lanka\u2019s commitments in financial services allow for an ENT to govern approval, registration and licensing of banks and other financial institutions, foreign branches and maximum foreign equity of 49 percent. Moreover, the entry for direct insurance provides for new establishments to be subject to government licensing. The relevant criteria are not further specified in the schedule. Foreign equity participation throughout the financial service sector is limited to 49 percent, except for reinsurance and retrocession where Sri Lanka has not accepted any bindings on commercial presence. \uf06c Tourism: No restrictions specified apart from those applicable horizontally. 6.11.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Financial services In 2002, out of 23 commercial banks in Sri Lanka, 12 were foreign banks. Foreign equity limits were raised from 49 percent to 60 percent in 2000, and eliminated in May 2002. There are no restrictions on foreign competition in banking, including from overseas branches, and foreign suppliers receive national treatment. However, a restriction which limits the scope of FDI even when 100 percent equity is allowed, is that foreign commercial banks are allowed to open branch offices in Sri Lanka subject to an ENT and approval by the Central Bank. Foreign investors are allowed to hold 100 percent equity in local banks subject to limits on individual share ownership. 49 Liberalization in the Sri Lankan financial services sector has extended to insurance as well. The state no longer has any commercial role in insurance. Foreign investment restrictions have been removed and limits on overseas re-insurance eased. Entry of insurance companies is unrestricted. Foreign branches must be lo- cally incorporated firms under the Companies Act of 1982. However, it is to be noted that resident Sri Lankans are prohibited from obtaining foreign insurance policies except for health and travel. Telecommunication services The state monopoly in basic telecommunications no longer exists and 100 percent foreign equity is allowed in the sector in Sri Lanka. As part of its liberalization programme, Sri Lanka adopted a new National Communica- tions Policy in 2003, which included provision of a liberal licensing regime to allow unrestricted competition from new, including foreign, entrants. However, the government indefinitely suspended the policy in August 2003, and the implementation status of the policy could not be ascertained. Transportation services The only restriction on foreign registered operators providing domestic air services in Sri Lanka is that 60 percent of their directors must be Sri Lankan. In shipping, the only foreign investment restriction is the for- eign equity limit of 60 percent for shipping agencies. However, state intervention in transportation remains substantial. The provision of air services is still dominated by the majority state-owned national carrier, Sri Lankan Airlines. Another state-owned company has the monopoly on airport services. Though some private- sector involvement was allowed in the provision of port services in 1998, since then there have not been any significant reforms. 6.11.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services constituted 57.1 percent of Sri Lanka\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007). Sri Lanka is a net service exporter with transportation and tourism accounting for majority of services exports. Other major services include wholesale and retail trade, transport and communication, banking and insurance. Tourism has wit- nessed rekindled foreign investment following the domestic peace initiatives. More efficient services delivery is a government priority, but several state utility monopolies exist, often incurring large losses. Notwithstanding the limitations inscribed in Sri Lanka\u2019s schedule, services liberalization is believed to be the key to attracting foreign investment and developing infrastructure in the country. Sri Lanka allows 100 percent foreign investment in the following services: banking, finance, insurance, stock-brokering, construc- tion of residential buildings and roads, supply of water, mass transportation, telecommunications, energy production and distribution, professional services and the establishment of liaison offices or local branches of foreign companies. These services are regulated and subject to approval by various government agencies. The screening mechanism is non-discriminatory and, for the most part, routine. This move towards liberaliza- tion goes beyond Sri Lanka\u2019s commitments at GATS and removes foreign equity restrictions on many sectors that had been placed therein. It may be mentioned that Sri Lanka believes that the GATS Article IV must effectively raise developing- country participation in the services trade. It has suggested that industrialized countries be required to pro- vide meaningful access in services of export interest to developing members, and to limit their liberalization requests to developing countries. Sri Lanka has moved beyond its GATS commitments by removing the cap on foreign equity in a num- ber of sectors including telecommunications", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7bb825ff-128e-49d0-8775-213c94541952": {"__data__": {"id_": "7bb825ff-128e-49d0-8775-213c94541952", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "99571306c23acdbdf81037458bd21f313a2b4475d47636e4f9e1ae586ecd16fb"}}, "hash": "99571306c23acdbdf81037458bd21f313a2b4475d47636e4f9e1ae586ecd16fb", "text": "and banking. It has not submitted any new offers in the GATS (2000) negotiations. 50 6.12 Thailand 6.12.1 Comments on Mode 3 commitments Thailand\u2019s GATS schedule covers all major service sectors except health. \uf06c Foreign equity limitations of 49 percent on commercial presence are scheduled for a range of professional services, such as legal, accounting and architecture, as well as for certain construction, education, environ- mental, tourism, recreational, cultural, sporting, maritime, rail and road transport services. \uf06c In other sectors, foreign equity limitations range from 20 percent to 49 percent for telecommunication services, and 25 percent to 49 percent for most banking and non-banking financial services (including insurance). \uf06c In financial services, although new branches are subject to discretionary licensing, \u2018grandfathering\u2019 provisions allow foreign bank branches operating in Thailand before July 1995, to open up two more branches. Access through locally incorporated banks is limited to the acquisition of shares of existing banks and foreign equity participation is limited to 25 percent. \uf06c Thailand has also listed MFN exemptions on telecommunications, transport and professional services. Thailand has emphasized ownership over other considerations. Services markets, except in infrastruc- tural services where more restrictive conditions were imposed, are quite open to foreign competition, but still, Thailand has retained its ability to implement WTO-consistent discriminatory industrial policies, even if foreign-equity ceilings were to be lifted. It is also one of the few cases where MA and NT are strongly linked. There is the impression that the overall emphasis is not on MA by itself, but in its relation to NT and the industrial and developmental policies embedded within. 6.12.2 Autonomous liberalization and trends in FDI Financial services Foreign equity limits were relaxed in 1997, for 10 years to allow foreign ownership of up to 100 percent (previously 25 percent) in commercial banks, finance companies and credit financiers. After 10 years, foreign investors were to be allowed to purchase additional equity or participate in equity recapitalization of financial institutions, unless their equity holding is less than 49 percent. Foreign investors who increased their equity to over 49 percent during this 10 year period were not required to sell their shares, but would not be able to purchase additional shares. In 1999, 22 foreign bank branches operated in Thailand. In 2001, three of them closed down and brought down the number of foreign bank branches to 18 in 2002. However, relaxation of foreign equity limits resulted in substantial majority ownership of four Thai commercial banks. At the end of 2002, foreign banks held 16 percent of total commercial bank assets of Baht 6.5 trillion (I USD equals around 33.5 baht) and this share has continued to rise. An encouraging step towards increasing foreign investments in the financial sector was taken in Janu- ary 2004, when the Thai Cabinet approved a new Financial Sector Master Plan (FSMP). This Plan was designed to increase competition by eliminating regulatory boundaries within the financial sector. The Plan classified financial institutions as either commercial banks able to provide all financial services except insurance, securi- ties trading and brokerage; or retail banks, which would focus on small and medium-sized enterprises and 51 lower-income customers. According to the Plan, retail banks can provide virtually all types of financial transac- tions with the same exceptions as commercial banks. The Plan allows foreign banks to operate as full branches under the same conditions as Thai commercial banks, but without the option of opening branch offices, or subsidiaries, which would also operate as Thai commercial banks. Over time, the Plan foresees foreign banks receiving permission to open 3-5 branch offices outside Bangkok, but no timeframe is specified. Thailand\u2019s TPR (2003) noted that the government\u2019s three-stage plan to encourage foreign investment in insurance which started in 1997, did not go beyond its second stage. At the first stage, 25 percent foreign equity participation in a joint venture with a local firm was allowed (in 1997). However, certain insurance com- panies exceed the 25 percent limit since they started operations in Thailand before the legislation became effective in 1992. They were allowed to keep their higher foreign equity participation under \u2018grandfathering\u2019 provisions. The largest life insurer in Thailand, with over half of the market, has a majority foreign ownership since this firm entered the Thai life insurance market before the enforcement of the current Life Insurance Act, and its acquired rights have been protected under grandfathering provisions. If proposed amendments get the nod of the parliament, the limit of foreign equity participation will increase to 49 percent, thus marking completion of the second stage. The contemplated third stage allows majority foreign equity participation within ten", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "09553b51-e14a-4e25-8f19-3ad4aeed4065": {"__data__": {"id_": "09553b51-e14a-4e25-8f19-3ad4aeed4065", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "194a8520579fee340a516f64411cd98b6e62a3b37a7c1109e10b8dbc4b306c68"}}, "hash": "194a8520579fee340a516f64411cd98b6e62a3b37a7c1109e10b8dbc4b306c68", "text": "years after the completion of the second stage liberalization. The bill is being considered at the ministerial level. However, this bill is indicative of the liberalization process in Thailand and the fact that Thailand has been pursuing domestic reforms which go beyond the commit- ments made by it at the GATS. Telecommunications Thailand launched a Master Plan for Telecommunications Development in 1997 to fully liberalize basic tele- communications by 2006. Existing concessions to foreign participants were to be converted to licences to encourage what the authorities saw as \u201cfree and fair\u201d competition in telecommunications. The Telecommunications Business Act 2001 reduced the foreign equity cap from 49 percent to 25 per- cent. However, the government announced in May 2002 that it would raise the ceiling back to 49 percent. Transportation Foreign investment in domestic land, waterway or air transportation, including domestic airlines, is restricted under the Foreign Business Act (1999) and is closed to non-Thai nationals or companies with majority foreign equity, unless approved by the cabinet. While the Act permits foreign equity participation of up to 60 percent (or 75 percent on a case-by-case basis), if two thirds of the firm\u2019s board of directors are Thai nationals, specific transport legislation seemingly prohibits majority foreign equity. In the case of domestic shipping and avia- tion, sectoral legislation also stipulates minimum Thai equity levels of 70 percent. Land ownership Although non-Thai businesses and citizens are not permitted to own land in Thailand unless the land is on government-approved industrial estates, and Thailand has submitted land ownership restrictions on foreign- ers, there has been some relaxation of this restriction. Under the 1999 amendment to the Land Code, foreign- ers who invest a minimum of 40 million baht (around US$ one million) are permitted to buy up to 1,600 square meters of land for residential use with the permission of the Ministry of Interior. Though many foreign businesses sign long-term leases instead, and then construct buildings on the leased land, this move towards liberalization of the GATS commitment is still noteworthy. 52 6.12.3 Policy space and commitments under GATS Services contributed 44.4 percent to Thailand\u2019s GDP in 2006 (World Bank 2007). The large share of FDI which goes into services is concentrated in the finance and retail trade. Transportation and communications are the other important services sectors. Thailand has introduced autonomous reforms, including higher foreign equity limits in banking. How- ever, foreign investment in most other service sectors remains limited to 49 percent ownership. In its latest TPR of November 2003, the WTO has taken note of Thailand\u2019s steady progress towards trade liberalization, and has observed that regulatory reforms geared to make domestic markets more competitive will raise productivity and attract FDI. Thailand has made a revised offer as part of the ongoing GATS (2000) negotiations, but the same have not been de-restricted and are thus unavailable in the public domain. Thailand seems to have liberalized beyond its GATS commitments in financial sector, and has also eased foreign land ownership restrictions subject to minimum investment. However, for other services sectors, there have not been any significant levels of liberalization as yet. The Thai Board of Investment has recognized basic transportation, infrastructure and services as key areas where investment needs to be promoted. In addition to legal limits on foreign ownership in certain sectors, Thai firms employ defences against foreign investment primarily through cross- and stable-shareholding arrangements. Such defences against hostile takeovers are typically applied against all potential investors, rather than against foreign potential investors alone. Companies are permitted to specify more strict limits on foreign ownership than those estab- lished by the government. In general, limits on foreign ownership and participation in the Thai economy have eased since the Asian Financial Crisis. 53 The experiences of the acceding countries to the WTO constitute a new and emerging area of research. The process of accession to the WTO has attracted attention not only in terms of the process per se with respect to its complexity and duration, but also in terms of outcomes and impacts such as benefits of WTO membership post accession, \u2018costs\u2019 faced by acceding countries in terms of relatively more stringent rules and so on.65 A particular concern has been raised with respect to the higher benchmarking and an attempt by the Working Party members to set ambitious templates for countries wanting to join the WTO in the future. Also, it has been claimed that benefits accruing from the developing country status have not been realized in practice despite the fact that most of these countries ranked low on per capita GDP and have a large proportion of their population", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "42717339-f861-4761-8a82-37063c8c053a