 ways of the range and extent of obligations which the NACs have committed themselves to in the process of accession. Previous research on variance between the total number of subsectors committed between different countries has shown that Nepal and Cambodia, both LDCs who acceded to the WTO post 1995, have committed to 76 and 93 sub sectors respectively as opposed to the 20 subsectors which were committed to on average by the LDCs during the Uruguay Round.67 Here, the total number of sectors/subsectors committed as also and the extent of NT and MA limitations in the schedules are used as the \u2018proxy for price\u2019, which NACs have paid in order to become a WTO member. In addition to this analysis, it is also useful to undertake a qualitative analysis of the nature of MA and NT limitations which can be another useful way of understanding the commitments of the NACs. 7. Policy space in GATS and select experiences of the newly acceding countries to the WTO 65 For a more detailed discussion on the issue, see for instance, Evenett, Simon, J. and Carlos A. Primo Braga (2005). \u201cWTO Accession: Lessons from Experience\u201d. Trade Note 22, International Trade Department, World Bank. 66 Anar Mammadov, WTO Accession Issues for SPECA countries, UNCTAD Presentation, http://europeandcis.undp.org/uploads/public/File/ YVERDON.WTOAccession_SPECA1.ppt, accessed 29 November 2008. 67 A similar pattern is discerned on account of agricultural and non-agricultural market access as well. See for details, Evenett, Simon, J. and Carlos A. Primo Braga (2005). \u201cWTO Accession: Lessons from Experience\u201d. Trade Note 22, International Trade Department, World Bank. 54 The schedule of specific commitments of the NACs exhibits the following features: [1] To reiterate the point raised previously, the sectoral and sub-sectoral coverage is more extensive than that of other developing countries. Thus, Cambodia has scheduled commitments in 11 sectors, China in 9 sectors, Nepal in 11 sectors and Kyrgyz Republic in 11 sectors. Sectors committed to liberalization include health, education, environmental services and financial services. The commitments for Bangla- desh (2), India (6), Pakistan (6), Philippines (4) and Sri Lanka (3) are much reduced. [2] An examination of the horizontal commitments of the NACs reveals again that barring some land owner- ship restrictions in the case of Cambodia, China and Nepal and restrictions on movement of natural per- sons, there are no limitations on market access or national treatment for foreign investments. In the case of Nepal, the need to obtain government permission prior to investing in the country has been listed as a national treatment limitation and a requirement for environmental impact assessment clearance for all services related activities. In the schedule of India for instance, collaboration with public sector enter- prises or government undertakings as a joint venture partner, preference to the foreign service provider offering the best terms for transfer of technology has been listed as a national treatment limitation. Malaysia again for instance has listed out a series of MA restrictions related to mergers and acquisitions and has NT restrictions if land is sought to be acquired for speculative or non-productive purposes which may conflict with the interest of the state. Also, preferences for indigenous population (Bumiputera) or indigenous status companies and institutions/trusts to meet the objectives of the National Economic Policy or National Development Policy have been kept unbound. Similarly, the Philippines has specified MA limitations which limit foreign equity in all sectors (except insurance) to a minority stake. Also, it has listed out NT conditions on accessing of domestic credit by foreign firms.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "03739833-f226-4f61-a757-1b47afd69306": {"__data__": {"id_": "03739833-f226-4f61-a757-1b47afd69306", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6a9a574a318415455fcdcfb5764a7219b3a4c70fcf6b62b943574df99fe97459"}, "2": {"node_id": "42717339-f861-4761-8a82-37063c8c053a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e199c4c795cc643f4b0cdaba9c620fcbf1eeb4da9751b38caf8f2097504ffeb5"}}, "hash": "7c755e9c831c52c886cd03b03556f339be8a3f2e275ff2d594dfffc33629fd18", "text": "Also, it has listed out NT conditions on accessing of domestic credit by foreign firms. Importantly, it must be borne in mind that for countries such as India, by limiting fewer sectors it has some policy space to regulate foreign investment in sectors still open for scheduling/negotiations. However, for the NACs due to the extensive nature of commitments, the policy space more or less does not exist in any substantive sense. [3] An examination of the sectoral commitments of the NACs reveals that on both counts of market access and national treatment limitations, the extent of liberalization is much wider and deeper. Let us now take", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2f9f102b-4e1b-4442-ab91-f32f676a81c3": {"__data__": {"id_": "2f9f102b-4e1b-4442-ab91-f32f676a81c3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f24e6674c3c0f5ac29e7c49c64d27fe66d78ffb0c581eeee5c8d59c4d20d64cf"}}, "hash": "f24e6674c3c0f5ac29e7c49c64d27fe66d78ffb0c581eeee5c8d59c4d20d64cf", "text": "a look at the schedules of the different NACs under consideration. Cambodia Market Access In legal services, the only MA restriction is related to commercial association with Cambodian law firms and restrictions on direct representation of clients in court. In specialized medical services, provision of services is permitted through joint ventures with Cambodian judicial services. In telecom services, the only MA limitation is of the requirement that the local shareholding has to be up to 49%. In banking and other financial services, commercial presence is granted only through authorized financial institutions and some services are subject to establishment of regulatory laws. In health services, the only MA limitation is related to the presence of one Cambodian director for technical matters. In tourism and travel related services, there are MA limitations relating to equity ceilings and economic needs criteria being met. National Treatment There are no NT restrictions except for a limited time exception of up to January 2009 in a few sub-sectors, which are set to expire in any case. 55 Nepal Most of the MA restrictions relate to foreign equity ceilings varying between 51% - 80%/joint venture require- ments and subject to the service provider being incorporated in Nepal. NT restrictions are mostly not scheduled with the exception of the telecom services wherein it has been mentioned that the majority of the board of directors of a joint venture should be Nepali nationals and NT limitations obtained on education services funded from state resources. China Market Access In the sectoral commitments, China has placed geographic (retailing services for instance) and quantitative MA restrictions in line with the countries\u2019 needs, some of which are time barred and would be removed in predefined periods following the accession of the country. In sectors such as accountancy, licensing require- ments have been listed out. Several sub-sectors have a joint venture requirement while permissive of majority shareholdings and some have minimum asset requirements in order to operate in China. In basic telecom services, ceilings of upto 50% have been set out as a condition for establishment. For construction and related engineering services China has put in an interesting requirement that for Chinese invested construction proj- ects, depending on need, permissions of the concerned provincial government would be required. This has meant a role for the provincial governments as well, albeit in a limited sense. For banking and other financial services, China has put in minimum asset requirements between USD 10-20 billion for establishment. National Treatment NT restrictions relate to minimum residency requirements. Majority of the personnel (for example in medical and dental services) are subject to nationality requirements. There are some regulatory conditions attached to onshore oil field services. Kyrgyz Republic Except for real estate services, services incidental to fishing, services related to distribution of electric en- ergy, postal services, air transport services (except maintenance and repair of aircraft) which have been kept unbound in Mode 3 for both MA and NT, there are no limitations on MA and NT. Primary education, higher education, and adult education services are funded from state resources. Additionally, there are no horizontal limitations on Mode 3 commitments as well and the services schedule can be seen as extensive market liber- alization commitments. While it is difficult to generalize across countries, it does appear that nearly all the NACs have not taken recourse to the flexibilities embedded in the GATS architecture to schedule limitations even in sectors such as health, education and environment, which are critical from the point of view of human development and therefore need appropriate government regulation. In some instances, the sectors have been opened up without the benefit of adequate experiences in either the setting up or maturing of the regulatory institu- tions, a typical case of placing the cart before the horse. Indeed, the GATS flexibilities were mainly intended to offer options to each country to be selective and adopt a sui generis approach to opening up in the services sector. This has obvious implications for policy space to operationalize developmental goals as in practice it is impossible for any country to reverse any of the commitments entered into in the WTO. 56 8.1 Looking ahead The services sector has emerged as a fulcrum of developmental dynamics in a number of Asian economies. Not only has the services sector become strategic in its contribution to GDP growth across Asia, but it is increasingly expected to also bear the responsibility of providing an inclusive character to GDP-growth. Given economy-wide efficiencies and positive spillover effects of a fully developed services sector, services are rec- ognised as a backbone for development having a catalytic character", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3fe3b279-4192-4d23-abc1-12dc314fd675": {"__data__": {"id_": "3fe3b279-4192-4d23-abc1-12dc314fd675", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bff13469e0c1fd5303c5eba8154f545a22bbbe7f27fb8f4a2f39dae9985a3d91"}}, "hash": "bff13469e0c1fd5303c5eba8154f545a22bbbe7f27fb8f4a2f39dae9985a3d91", "text": "for boosting all round growth. Understanding trends in the liberalization of the services trade needs to take into account liberalization at the bilateral, regional and multilateral levels for a comprehensive assessment. There has been an ongoing debate as to whether or not liberalization of the services trade would constrain the policy space and capacity of governments to regulate services to achieve vital human development objectives. At another level there has been the issue of the nature and extent to which governments have sought to utilize the policy available in the investment rules under GATS, while scheduling their commitments with a special focus on NACs to the WTO. Within the limitations outlined earlier, this study attempts to offer some insights to this cluster of issues. UNCTAD (2006) in its study suggests that reliance on GATS schedules alone, underestimates the extent to which countries have opened up their services sectors to FDI. The analysis of autonomous liberalization commitments on a host of services made by countries included in the sample, shows that FDI-liberalization commitments undertaken by them at an autonomous level are deeper in comparison to the commitments undertaken by them under GATS on the same set of services. This study therefore echoes the conclusions drawn by the UNCTAD (2006) analysis. In comparison, the commitment made by the sampled countries under GATS while moving further on the autonomous liberalization route in the larger macroeconomic context of galvanizing domestic savings and capital formation shows that: \uf06c The GATS process has the potential to enable the developing countries to encourage capacity creation of their local workforce, as evidenced in some of the sectoral schedules of the countries examined. Nepal for instance has sought to protect local entrepreneurship by encouraging joint ventures between for- eign investors and Nepalese nationals. Similar provisions can be found in Sri Lanka where the only the restriction on foreign registered operators providing domestic air services in Sri Lanka, is that 60 percent of their directors must be Sri Lankan. 8. Conclusion 57 \uf06c Larger and powerful developing countries like China have utilized the GATS process to signal the level of restraint they would like to exercise when opening key sectors such as banking in the context of achieving their social goals of universal banking. The Republic of Korea too, has restricted market access of foreign banks to its markets by attaching a number of conditions such as requirement of a separate licence for each foreign branch, requirements relating to minimum operating funds and the requirement of having expertise in international banking business. India has also selectively liberalized its services sector. \uf06c Further, the GATS process has allowed countries to keep themselves unbound in services where they believe they lack sufficient regulatory framework. Nepal for instance has kept itself unbound for a series of financial services until it is better to carry out an assessment of its domestic preparedness. \uf06c In general, it does appear for the selected countries that the GATS framework has succeeded in permit- ting commitments to retain sufficient space for development policies, as NT is, in many cases, unbound, and some NACs have been able to include horizontal restrictions. However, in the case of some NACs the coverage of NT measures seems limited to certain sectors and countries and quantitative limitations have not been utilized in their schedules. The NACs\u2019 schedules show that market liberalization through GATS has been wider in the number of sectors involved, and deeper, in the extent of full commitments, both in terms of MA and NT. Moreover, important sectors for human development such as health, educa- tion and environmental services, have been systematically liberalized barring some exceptions. Overall, based on inter-country comparison of schedules it appears that the NACs may have been subject to greater pressures for liberalization and opening up. \uf06c Efficient supply of services arguably is a sine qua non for promotion of economic growth promoting human development. While liberalization offers opportunities for increased economic growth and de- velopment, an un-regulated liberalization process can threaten developmental goals such as universal access to essential services. Accordingly, the Sub-Commission on Human Rights in its Resolution 2001/4 called upon \u201cgovernments and international economic policy forums to ensure that, in the formulation, interpretation and implementation of policies in relation to the liberalization of trade in services, the liberalization of trade in services does not negatively impact enjoyment of human rights by all persons without discrimination\u201d.68 \uf06c Services liberalization in Mode 3 is expected to lead to increased opportunities for foreign investment. Targeted and well directed FDI can potentially upgrade infrastructure, introduce new technologies, generate employment opportunities, reduce the burden on government resources", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ab80e4d2-99cb-4f29-bc37-4ea42a29ace9": {"__data__": {"id_": "ab80e4d2-99cb-4f29-bc37-4ea42a29ace9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3f41cc12af0094268f530d702ab80bf9b2bfd008e6c95b757f4d33833d9becb5"}, "3": {"node_id": "17c23440-4cc8-4d57-b499-e202aa972469", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fe0890aed9c143ffd801590db4a1250fe4a6924cc69f72512e6ed874487f64bf"}}, "hash": "ddd5b59cad1c483143d54750564c976fb23e96d0004487d663344909751d6e87", "text": "and be useful in playing a vital complementary role to services provision by the public sector, in many instances. At the same time, private monopolization of public monopoly services can have adverse consequences for development. \uf06c The regulators thus need to ensure that trade liberalization policies take into account the state\u2019s respon- sibility to respect and fulfil human development. Hence, while preservation of policy space can enhance human development, it is also believed that \u201ca world trade regime friendly to human development would provide domestic policy space and give developing countries flexibility to make institutional and other innovations. Such policy space should take precedence over MA considerations, even as the trade regime continues to recognize that MA can make an important contribution to human development in specific situations and for specific sectors and issues\u201d. 69 68 United Nations Social and Economic Service (2001). 69 Malhotra (2004). 58 References Adlung, Rudolf and Martin Roy (2005). \u201cTurning hills into mountains? Current commitments under the GATS and prospects for change\u201d. Staff Working Paper, Economic Research and Analysis Wing, WTO, http://www.wto. org/english/res_e/reser_e/ersd200501_e.htm Chang, Ha-Joon (2005). \u201cPolicy Space in Historical Perspective- with special reference to Trade and Industrial Policies\u201d. http://www.networkideas.org/featart/sep2005/Policy_Space.pdf China Daily (2006). \u201cThe Education Industry\u2019s WTO Commitments\u201d. http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/ bizchina/2006-04/18/content_570805.htm Corrales-Leal, Werner (2007). \u201cBasic Concepts and Proposals on the Use of Policy Spaces in Trade - Supported Strategies for Sustainable Development\u