d Tourism. Apart from the horizontal restrictions in Column 2, Maritime Transport has been kept unbound. Economically meaning- ful exemptions cover NT measures based upon co-production bilateral and multilateral agree- ments in Audiovisual Services, Land, Maritime and Internal Waterway Transport. Annex 1: Schedules of developing Asian countries 63 Country (1) Horizontal commitments (2) MA sectoral commitments (3) NT sectoral commitments (4) MFN exemptions (5) China Scheduled a horizontal limitation in the form of establishment. Foreign investors can enter the Chinese market only through foreign- owned enterprises, JVs, or representative offices. Therefore, the acquisition of existing Chinese companies can be restricted by the local regulation on competition, M&As. As regards NT, subsidies kept unbound in Au- diovisual, Aviation, and Medical Services sectors, and some restrictions introduced on land ownership. Scheduled most sub- sectors except Research and Development, Recreational Services, and Space Transport. Comprehensive phase- outs of geographic and ownership restrictions. However, JV require- ments, without foreign-equity ceilings, are most common across the schedule, except for Telecommunications, Maritime and Air Transport, where foreign control is restricted. Internal Waterway Transport is unbound. For other types of Transportation, Tourism, and Franchising, further restrictions are not included. Scheduled business scope limitations and ENTs for very specific sub-sectors, mostly with the aim to limit the commitment of those sectors. In Construction, however, limitations in business scope apply in a similar way, as an ENT. Apart from the horizon- tal restrictions in Column 2, prudential restrictions in several sectors (trans- parency, residence, and registration/certification requirements). Also scheduled: l\ufffd Employment requirement in Health Services; l\ufffd Unbound in Educational Services; l\ufffd Geographic and busi- ness scope limitation (only for foreigners) in Travel Agency and Tour Operator; services l\ufffd Export requirements for Aircraft Mainte- nance. Exemption to Maritime Transport companies of countries with bilateral agreements with China. 64 Country (1) Horizontal commitments (2) MA sectoral commitments (3) NT sectoral commitments (4) MFN exemptions (5) India Scheduled one NT restriction, giving preference to suppliers/ entities that offer best terms of transfer of technology, but only for PPPs. Commitments in Busi- ness Services, Commu- nications, Construction, Finance Services, Health, and Tourism Services. Within these sectors, access is granted in all cases, except for Communications and Finance, but only through incorporation in the country, and with a foreign-equity ceiling of 51 percent. This measure is aimed at promoting foreign investment in new businesses and allowing control of companies, but also ensuring the participa- tion of Indian interests in the new company. Committed in Telecommunication Services, subject to licensing requirements and with a foreign-equity ceiling of 25 percent. Also committed to openning up the distribution of Audiovisual products, but only through a representative office and with quantitative limita- tions on the number of products. Allows representations of foreign insurance companies, with strict limitations on their scope of business. In Banking, 12 licences granted yearly to foreign banks (for both present and new entrants) to carry on branch operations. However, limits on acqui- sition by foreign banks, of outstanding stakes in other licensed financial companies (eliminating the possibility of any takeovers), as well as on the market share of foreign companies in the Banking sector to 15 percent. For Other Financial Services, MA allowed under JVs with a 51 percent foreign-equity ceiling. Apart from the horizontal restrictions in Column 2, no further restrictions included, and \u201cnone\u201d scheduled, except in the following sectors: l\ufffd Telecommunications: Unbound. l\ufffd Audiovisual Services: ENT (Certification of the quality of the product). l\ufffd Financial sector: \ufffd (a)\ufffdUnbound in Insurance. \ufffd (b) In Banking, the appointment of Chairman and members of the Board requires approval from the RBI. The RBl shall also constitute a Local Advisory Board on small and medium- sized enterprises (SMEs) and exports.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f1509a6b-3dc0-4ee7-8ee4-f768e6a185fc": {"__data__": {"id_": "f1509a6b-3dc0-4ee7-8ee4-f768e6a185fc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "08a606126ad8eb44cca91066a9b9d0bf2869f2a2449522bf414ad2dc37322edb"}, "2": {"node_id": "4544e794-16b5-428a-b27f-3836216fdbb3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "415630eab8d74bc96da69d2c852f8b9ce107c348e3e9ffdf9850f27f7a874244"}}, "hash": "c28e621c1c10ce5adeb060f10a1d412b6112874c8dacf2e53c8dc2b442103ec7", "text":