s unbound. For other Transport Services, the majority of the board members are required to be Thai nationals. For most of the sched- ule, NT provided for companies that comply with limitations on MA for foreign equity. Therefore, as far as the company maintains its Thai \u201cnationality\u201d, it can benefit from Thailand\u2019s discriminatory policies. Through this commit- ment, Thailand allows local companies to keep benefiting from NT discriminations, while, at the same time, enabling them to mobilize foreign capital to furnish their capitalization needs as far as those processes do not result in the takeover/acquisition of the company by foreign interests. This is one of the few cases where a country\u2019s sectoral commitments are \u201cdeeper\u201d than at the horizontal level. Also, NT linked to MA restrictions. This type of scheduling ensures predictability while maintaining a very broad policy scope. NT is unbound for Maritime and Air Transport. MFN exemption included in favour of the USA in the sectors covered by their bilateral agreement. Also scheduled an exemption in cargo-sharing with China and Viet Nam, and in international road transportation, on a reciprocity basis. Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific Colombo Office 23 Independence Avenue Colombo 7 Sri Lanka Tel: +94 11 4526400 Fax: +94 11 4526410 Email: rcc@undp.org Website: http://www.undprcc.lk", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a55d8559-91b8-40b9-9a50-180185186809": {"__data__": {"id_": "a55d8559-91b8-40b9-9a50-180185186809", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/private-sector-engagement-helps-keep-communities-safe", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_e