ware: The Use and Misuse of Regressions in Explaining Economic Growth\u201d Policy research brief Nov/2007 no. 5, International Poverty Centre, and \u201cCleaning Up the Kitchen Sink: Growth Empirics When the World Is Not Simple\u201d, Wesleyan Economic Working Papers, No: 2006-004, http://repec.wesleyan.edu/ 6 Sanjay G. Reddy, \u201cSafety Nets for the Poor: A Missing International Dimension?\u201d in Pro- Poor Macroeconomic Policies, Giovanni Andrea Cornia, ed, New York: Palgrave Macmillan and UNRISD, 2006. 7 Pasha and Palanivel, 2003, p. 329 and Palanivel, 2008 (mimeo) 8 Ibid, p.329 9 Pasha and Palanivel, 2003, Ibid, P.331 10 Ricardo Hausman, Dani Rodrik and Andr\u00e9s Velasco (2004). \u2019Growth Diagnostics\u2019. mimeo, Harvard University. 11 Rathin Roy, Antoine Heuty, and Emmanuel Letouz\u00e9. \u201cFiscal Space for Public Investment: Towards a Human Development Approach\u201d. Paper prepared for the G-24 technical meeting, Singapore, September 13-14, 2006 12 The Samoa country study praises the VAT as contributing substantially to growth of revenue. In India, certain governments have inaugurated VAT. Of the other countries that we have studies for (Iran, Sri Lanka, Bhutan) none has VAT. 13 Pasha and Palanivel, 2003, Ibid, P.331 14 Joseph Stiglitz, \u201cThe Phelps factor\u201d, http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/joseph_stiglitz/2006/12/the_phelps_factor.html 15 Rudiger Dornbusch and Stanley Fischer, \u201cModerate Inflation\u201d, The World Bank Economic Review, Vol. 7, No. 1, pp. 1-44 (January 1993, 16 Edwards and Savastano, \u201cExchange Rate Policies\u201d (2002), cited in thematic paper on exchange rate policy.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f99498cb-847f-407c-ac85-2b9956dfb36e": {"__data__": {"id_": "f99498cb-847f-407c-ac85-2b9956dfb36e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.